Message-Id: <8805191924.AA04419@straits.rutgers.edu>
To: SCA@ai.ai.mit.edu
Subject: Fencing: a bit of philosophy
Reply-To: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu


Greetings all!

Over the past couple years, there has been an active discussion of
fencing among the officers and Curia of the East.  The Fencers had
proposed to Curia that a new award be created for fencing.  This award
has since been created.  However, during this discussion, a number of
rather interesting points were made about fencing, the SCA, and how
they ought to go together.  Personally, I see no problem with fencing
in the Society, as longas it is done well, and in period style with
research to back it up.  The Eastern fencers, for the most part, are
exemplary in these regards.  I would, however, like to present some
thoughts for discussion.  I don't necessarily agree with all of them,
but I think they do represent the opinion of a large part of the SCA,
and explain why many gentles feel so strongly that fencing does not
belong in the Knowne World.

The SCA was founded to (re)create an idealized view of medieval
Europe.  Its center, from day one of year one has been the noble
armored fighter.  Our ideals of chivalry and honor, our social
structure of fealty and feif, grow from the code of the knight of the
late Middle Ages.  In short, the armored warrior holds a special place
in the SCA.  Many people with whom I have discussed fencing find that
activity the antethesis of what the SCA means to them, and therefore
find fencing unsuitable as a major activity in the Society.

I have seen and discussed the documentation for fencing in period, and
I would not dream of questioning its provenence.  However, the
"period" of the SCA is not really "pre-1600".  That is just a
convenient number which the BoD added to Corpora a few years back to
try and control thing to an extent.  The period of the SCA is a much
vaguer notion, which differs from place to place.  For most SCAdians I
have spoken to, the period of the SCA is the age of the armored
knight.  In that culture, and in the ethical code that comes with it,
noblemen do not brawl in the streets with foils, they fight on the
field of honor with sword and lance.  The paragon of the medieval
warrior is the chivalrous and honorable knight.  The paragon of the
fencer is The Three Musketeers, and their dirty tricks.  I have been
told by a fencer at a tournament "Chivalry has no place in the list of
fence."  This attitude seems to run exactly counter to the fundamental
ideas of the SCA.  I do not believe this attitude is prevalent, but I
do think many non-fencers perceive fencing in that light, and
disapprove of it for that reason: it just doesn't fit in the SCA.

The answer to this criticism is, of course, to show that fencing does
fit.  Create of fencing a sport fit for a nobleman, with the honor and
courtesy which should be present in any list, and most will applaud
as they would any new addition to the SCA.  Research and document the
styles and methods of the art, and fencing becomes as legitimate an
art as any.  There will still be many who do not agree that fencing
belongs in the Society, and probably a majority who feel it should
never be more than a fringe activity: the philosophical conflict with
their ideal of the Society is simply too strong, and since the center
of the Society IS in the age of armor, that ideal must determine the
course of the Society as a whole.



