Subject: How to choose Royalty
Reply-To: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu


Lady Siobhan ni hEodhusa describes the Mists' experiment in Coronet
Tourney.

Many have lamented the reservation of roayl rank to fighters and their
consorts, and I can remember many discussions of various other ways of
bestowing the Crown.  (Gee, this ties in real nicely to the Philosophy
of Fencing letter I just sent!).  One big problem with any method
beside a tournament is the probable of judging.  In a tournament, it's
real easy to decide who won: it's the guy standing up at the end.  You
argue that he cheated, that he fought dishonorably, that he is slime
and scum and unfit to wipe your shoes on, but you can't deny the fact
that he won.  How can any other competition be judged so absolutely?
How can we guarantee that the judging of any arts competition could
possibly be fair?  There lies anarchy.  The arts in the SCA are
fraught with bitter politics as it is; can you imagine what would
happen if the Crown were at stake?  

Choosing our Kings and Queens from the bashers has its problems, but
it is fair in an important way, and it is considerably more authentic
than any other system: The SCA is supposed to be a military
aristocracy.  That's what feudalism is all about.


