Greetings;
   Alternation between fencing/rattan fighting does not solve the problem
of kingship - what's the difference whether a king earns his title with
a piece of wood or a rod of steel?  When fencing type weapons were used
in the past, the kings of the time waged war with mercenary armies and
cannon.  Before this, during the time of broadswords, kings often led
armies personally, and knew full well how to use their weapons on the
battle field.
   I do not intend to say that the king should become so solely by winning
a tournament, indeed, I certainly believe that the king should be required
to at least enter a certain amount of arts contests and should perhaps
be required to do fairly well there; in other words, the king should be a
well-rounded individual, not a stick jock only.  But alternating fencing
with rattan won't work.  I am interested in fencing, but do not believe
that Crown Tourney should ever be a fencing bout.  I believe that rattan
fighting represents a far greater part of the time period we all live in
and that it is more real than fencing in that historically this form of
fighting was around for a much longer period of time than fencing was.
-  In service to the East, Robert of Ferness, Seneschal of the Dominion
   of Myrkfaelinn

