Subject: SCA: Fencing


	As a mundane fencer who has made the transition to SCA
fencing, I can discuss a little bit about the problems both political
and practical.

First, as far as the Bod is concerned, Fencing is determined by
Kingdom standards (although they do have a new Laurel Marshal of Fence,
Don Tyvar Moondragon).  Thus, the primary problem is convincing a King
(and an Earl Marshal) that such a fencing group could be set up, and
really won't cause them any problems, quite possible by volunteering
to be Kingdom Marshal of Fence.  

As far as setting up safty standards for fencing, we have an easy
place to start, USFA safty rules.  The Bod also requires additional
protection for the back of the head, and we almost certainly want to
require equivalent protection rather than mundane fencing jackets, but
mundane fencing jackets with tunics tossed over are a place to start.

As far as learing how to fence in a period style is concerned, we have
several good sources.  They primary way that Lord Danulf (our esteemed
moderator) and I have been doing it is by using modern fencing
techniques and experimenting with doing them in the round, using the
left hand as a blocking insrument (currently East Kingdom standards
allow you to use (1) a leather glove, (2) a parry dagger, (3) a
buckler, (4) a second rapier (called case of rapier) and (5) a cloak.
They also allow experimentation with some other forms, such a beer
mug, but that is not as commonly done).  I am currently playing with
the stop thrust, which is a very interesting technique when done in
the round.  Of course, SCA fencing is done without right-of-way or
electronic scoring, so double kills are much more common.  We also
make a distiction between a kill and taking a limb, as they do in the
rattan lists.  

The second method of learning to fence involves looking back at period
fencing manual.  Yes, we do have instruction written in period
(primarily Italian sources, Fabris and Cappo Farro [sp?]) from before
1600, and a number of English ones from shortly after.  Thus, you do
not need to be cavalier to fence, its just that many cavaliers choose
to fence, which is more period for them, thus making the cavalier
fencers more noticable [not that cavalier persona's aren't noticable
in the first place].  Baron Patri has several of the English manuals
on microfiche and will make paper copies for a reasonable cost (the
cost varies, but is about $5/book).  Write to me if you are
interested.  Don Tyvar also has a rapier manual which is specifily
geared to SCA (Anstiorian) fencing.  I don't have my copy here, but I
will try and get that information to anyone who is interested.  

I, of course, could go on for hours on the subject, but I am running
late to Burrogh (college) meeting and dance class, so I will bid you
Peace and fairwell.


