Subject:      Mundane fencing
To:           SCA@AI.AI.MIT.EDU


I was surprised to hear that fencing has been "outlawed" anywhere in the
SCA--but stranger things have happened.  I would like to clarify some of
the more mundane aspects of fencing.  I am an SCA fencer, as well as a
mundane fencer.  I have been fencing in the mundane competitve world
for 15 years, and I have only heard of two serious injuries.  One was a
high school fencer who took a broken blade through the thigh (and lived
to fence again), the other is the unfortunate incident at the
Olympics? World Championships? where an epee fencer took a broken blade
through the mask (fatally).  I have been keeping in touch with the fencing
news and would be surprised if things have been happening that I was
unaware of.  All mentions of fencers who have recently died seem to be
limited to mundane reasons, like car accidents and heart attacks.

On the lighter side of things, the fencing world is constantly changing
(electric sabre at Nationals this year--for division II finals).  More
sturdy lames and more flexible blades (less likely to snap) are being
improved all the time.  Mundane or SCA, the worst fencing injuries I've
ever had are bruises and an occasional twisted ankle (from falling over
my own feet).  Maybe the West can take another look at the situation.

As far as fencing armor, mundane protection (or the equivalent), preferably
covered with garb is the norm, with the additional of: a glove on the off
hand, back of the head protection(we fence in the round), and additional
throat protection.

Now, on a personal level, I have observed the same phenomina in SCA fencing
as in fighting.  Some people have to be hit far too hard to get their
attention.  Others calibrate at one level, and fight at another.  I find
myself worrying if fencing will go the way of fighting and fencers will have
to wear more armor for their own protection.  My (current) favorite solution
to the problem (in the East):  require fencers to use *lighter* foil blades
instead of epee blades  (currently either is acceptable).  It is impossible
to hit as hard with a foil as with an epee.  Given the same amount of force
behind the blow, the foil will *give* and bend far more than an epee.

Sorry I've been so wordy, but I wanted to set the record straight.  Some of us
SCAdians take this mundane fencing stuff seriously.

                                I remain,
                                  Elektra Leonidas

