Subject: 'light lists' and blow escalation
To: sca@ai.ai.mit.EDU
X-VMS-To: IN%"sca@ai.ai.mit.edu",WELLING

I think that most fighters would agree that blow calibration levels and
armor standards have been rising for years.  In my experience (I've been
fighting for about 7 years) the rise has been pretty steady.  For as long
as I can remember people have been worrying about it and trying (without
success) to slow it down.

The trend should come as no surprise, however;  fighting is set up to reward
people for winning and increasing your personal calibration level by a hair
always gives you a bit of an edge in a fight.  The only force holding back
the trend is restraint based on chivalry and honor.  It's been pretty
effective;  after all it's taken 20 years to reach current calibration levels.
I don't think it can ever be totally effective, however;  it's just not
a rigid enough barrier.

This suggests to me that efforts to start 'light fighting' groups are doomed
to failure.  No matter how good the intentions, the basic rules of human
nature will apply and calibration levels will creep up.  Fencing was started
up in this Kingdom (the East) to fill just this role, but I understand that
the local variants of "light!" and "glancing!" have already started to appear
in fencing bouts.

So, let me suggest an alternative that I'm sure will meet with roars of
approval (or roars of some kind, anyway).  Would it be possible to decide
what level of blow was excessive and then not acknowledge anything heavier?
This would immediately introduce a sort of inverse rhino-hiding, (Whap!
"Light, my Lord!" Whap! "Heavy!" Whap! "Glancing!") but at least it would
provide an excuse for not falling down that would push blow levels down
rather than up. 

The question of how to choose the 'excessive' level immediately arises.
In response, I would point out that we don't have a mechanism for setting
the force of a minimal killing blow either.  Different people and different
groups would have different maximum levels, just as they have different
minimums now.  We would just be left with a situation where the tendency
would be for the maximum to drift *down*.

(Of course, it would be simple to build a machine that would deliver
a standard killing or excessive blow, but one off-the-wall idea per post
is enough).

		Yours in the Service of Chaos in the Marshallate,
		Magnus de Cnoc an Iora, Debatable Lands, East Kingdom
		(Joel Welling; welling@a.psc.edu)

