Remember back in the old days -- a week or two ago! -- when this list was
deluged by comments about dancing?  And we started to hear rumblings of "I
thought this was the SCA distribution list, not sca.dance"?

Those rumblings did not, by and large, come from people who have had much
experience with other newsgroups and distribution lists.  Each such group has
to evolve its own norms and standards, but some things are fairly common from
group to group:  One of these is the way topics ebb and flow.  Dancing didn't
stay the topic of the day, and Paganism won't.

If you aren't interested in the topic which is currently swamping the list --
and there will often be one -- DON'T COMPLAIN ABOUT IT.  It's not useful and
it's bad manners besides.  The volume is there because the interest is there.
Wait.  It'll pass soon enough.  (If the topics stay uninteresting, you're
probably subscribed to the wrong list.)  Alternatively, if there's something
you'd rather discuss, just do so.  Like-minded people will be happy to respond.
I'm not going to turn this message into a lecture on general netiquette; it's
obvious that most of the participants don't need it.  But for those few of you
who are relatively new to this sort of exchange -- if the topic doesn't
interest you stay out of it or change the subject.  But please don't send
messages of the form "I'm tired of this subject and wish you would stop".  It's
ill-mannered, somewhat akin to doing the same thing in person.  (Note:  If the
*tone* of the discussion becomes offensive it *is* appropriate to send the
offender mail directly, asking that it be changed.  Don't send the request to
the distribution list.)

I beg the pardon of the readers for going on at this length in a manner
analogous to the one I've been calling inappropriate.  As I said, if this group
continues to thrive it will develop its own standards -- but I expect it will
be more likely to thrive if we tend to stick to what other newsgroups have
taught us is pragmatic netiquette.

--Dani of the Seven Wells

