Really on the subject of "rolling back time" for fighting --

Hmm. This is getting to be a popular idea. Patri and I have talked about this
several times. There are two ways to do this, which boil down to the same thing.
First, we could create a completely separate list, for "light fighting",
where the rules would be a bit different, and the custom would be a *lot*
different. Second, we could set up a sort of mini-society of fighters who
agree that, when fighting each other at least, they will use a lighter
calibration than is customary in the Society today. Either way, there would
be a much higher emphasis on chivalry in fighting.

There would be some problems, of course. Ideally, we would want to roll back
the armor requirements as well, and this might present legal problems. Having
the armor requirements this high at one point, can we safely "roll them
back"? At the least, *someone* would bring this argument up, valid or not.
Also, there's really no way to police this new list with rules. In other
words, how do you define "not fighting chivalrously enough"? Basically, it
would have to be policed by all of the members, and by an honor system 
even stronger than the one currently in effect in the Society.

Still and all, I think that it's a fine idea. I've never become a fighter
for several reasons, the main one being that I can't *move* in armor that
is safe in the current lists. Being primarily a dancer, I can't cope with
*that* much added weight and constriction. Rolling back the customs and
armor requirements might bring some people like me into the fray (and I
would really like to at least be *able*, on general principles). Putting
a stronger emphasis on chivalry and style could do nothing other than
reflect well on the Society.

*Are* there people out there who are interested in this idea? Are there
people with opinions about whether it is possible or not? Let's hear from
you -- I'm beginning to think that there is sufficient interest to get
something like this started.

                            -- Justin du Coeur



I think that this is an excellent idea.  It might even draw in persons
who are interested in fighting, but not interested in increased medical
bills (like myself).  

Now, it's hard to be chivalrous when you're surrounded by 500 maniacs
wielding the moral equivalent of baseball bats, but in single combat,
I believe that chivalry ought to be more important than brute force.
Eduardo and Justin's ideas are excellent ones.  I think that if more 
attention was paid to chivalry and the art of swordplay and less to 
how hard you can whack someone upside the head, many people might 
reconsider going into fighting.  I know I would.

No flames, please.  Yes, I realize that there is more to fighting than
how hard you can whack someone upside the head.  I have nothing against 
fighting in its current form for melee and group fights.  However, in 
single combat, it lacks something of the romanticism that I like to see 
within the SCA.

