Subject: Pennsic archery, past and present
In-Reply-To: <May.16.21.54.44.1988.2188@zydeco.rutgers.edu>

Past:  Last summer, at Pennsic, I was able to get in two hours of practice each
morning.  For me this was the best part of archery there.  In Pittsburgh our
practices amount to an hour and a half once a week (we're trying to expand that
a bit during the summer, but the scheduling problems are formidable), and that
is barely enough to maintain one's skills, let alone improve them.  I realize
that better and more experienced archers are more likely to want interesting
new novelty shoots, but I'm not at that stage yet.

The main problem with the running of the lists last summer was the amount of
down-time:  For reasons which included occasional requisitions of half the
targets for other purposes, the amount of time spent retrieving and looking for
arrows, and lots more archers than shooting positions, far more time was spent
waiting than shooting.  Yet I'm told that last summer was considered a marvel
of efficiency and organization -- and I don't seriously doubt it.

Novelty shoots:  What this suggests to me is that the search for new novelty
shoots should take a back seat to the extremely difficult job of just keeping
the basics (practice time, Ikacs, the war points) running.  Not that they
should be scrapped, but that ambition should be checked by practicality:
archery at the war doesn't have much to work with in the way of resources.

This year's war point:  I've expressed my doubts as to the practicality of the
moving target, but people here that I've spoken to think that the problem with
it is not its technical practicality but its logistics.  They suggest that it
will involve even more overhead (nonshooting) time than the old speed shoot.
(Also, a number of people have suggested that it is likely to result in a lot
of broken arrows.)

--Dani of the Seven Wells

