I, Eduardo Bardi, having returned to the SCA in the last 2 months, having 
originally joined in 1978 and participating through about 1982, see some 
interesting changes since I last was in Carolingia.

MANY fewer of the "old guard" seem to come to dance practice regularly.  Yes,
I know. They know all the dances, or most of them anyway.  After 10-15 years
of going to dance practice, let someone else do it.  My professional career
involves much more of my time now.  And other reasons.  Nonetheless, I always
found that I learned the dances better as a novice, and enjoyed them more when
I could be in the company of experienced dancers.  Even now, I would enjoy
dance practice a lot more if more of the elders showed up.  There are lots of
other benefits other than dancing as well.  Interaction between old and new
becomes easier, people know each other better, it decreases factionism, one
has the opportunity to learn about manners, ettiquette, and flirting in an
informal setting.  It also helps set a good example for the younger groups.

On Fighting.  When I was a novice fighter, Baron Patri had just about totally 
stopped fighting.  Fighting styles were changing, he said.  People were 
hitting harder, more armor was needed (meaning that people were going to be 
hitting harder meaning more armor was going to be needed, ad infinitum), 
finesse was going out the window, there were many more swordjocks, and fewer 
gentlemen fighting strictly for the honor of a lady.  I agreed somewhat, but 
I enjoyed fighting, I only had to wear a helm (I think that I had the last 
double freon helm around these parts, and a good one it was too) a cup, knee 
and elbow pads, and some sort of kidney protection.  More armor was 
recommended, but not required.  I was a reasonably good fighter, too, and beat 
my share of knights up and down the East Kingdom and Atlantia.  I currently 
feel like Patri used to.  I have attended some fighting practices over the 
last years while I haven't been an active member, and I have talked to quite a 
number of people.  My developed opinion is that people are hitting WAY too
hard, armor requirements have gone through the roof correspondingly as people
get more and more likely to get really hurt, and the percentage of swordjocks
has gone up again.  If I begin fighting again, then I would be interested in
trying to start up a movement to roll fighting "back in time" so to speak.  I
would favor seeing a style that favored lighter "cleaner, more precise" blows,
less armor, and serious attention to the "finer details".   Having fighters
only able to participate in tournaments if they have the favor of a lady who
is attending the tournament, and giving prizes to the lady might be good ideas
as well. Perhaps a stronger reliance on "Ladies Champion Tournaments" would be 
a good idea.

	Well, I'll just sit here on this for now, wait for the hard rain to 
start falling :-), and save more writing till later.  

I will be very interested in what different kinds of responses might arise 
from this.
		
"Service"
		-Eduardo Bardi
		-Eddie



