The only way to improve people's first experiences with the society is for
*everyone* to work at it. The problem, of course, is that the groups that
really care about new people aren't the problem; it's the groups that are
well set in their ways, who don't feel the need for new blood, who probably
scare off the largest fraction. All we can do is to remind them that new
blood is good for any group, and that, in the long run, the effort will pay
off.

Also, remember that there is an economy of scale involved here. Carolingia,
for instance, is large enough to have several fighters who care enough to
bring spare armor to fighting practice (there may even be loaner armor --
I'm not sure, not being a fighter). Likewise, there is Barony-owned fencing
gear for loans, and tons of spare garb, mostly in the hands to the burroughs
(the college groups, where it's needed most). A smaller, younger group is far
less likely to have the money to purchase group-owned stuff, and there will
be fewer cast-offs to loan to people. In that kind of a case, one is 
dependent on people loaning their personal gear, and this usually results
in a few people making *many* loans, resulting in the fast erosion of such
gear.
							-- Justin du Coeur

