Good gentles, it itruly saddens my heart to hear of people who have 
run across problems like this in getting involved with the SCA or any
aspect of it.  I know not who this particular person is, or what part
of the country he is from, but I hope he tries again.  Whoever you are,
if you live in or near the San Francisco Bay area, I can help.  Sir 
Hilary of Serendip brings loaner armor to Bart practice Tuesdays and
Thursdays, and there is an unarmored practice for those just getting
started, or who don't have a huge household to support them being held
in Mountain View on Wednesday nights.  Write to me for details at
  {sun, decwrl} ...!quintus!laurie.  Now, all you good folk in other
parts of the country, what can we do to see that this sort of thing
happens as little as possible?  (not just the fighting, of course)
This year's newbies could be fighters within a year; they will be Shire
and Baronial officers in two or three, when Old Established Shireperson
moves up to Kingdom office or gets their Pelican and retires.  I
remember clearly how I showed up to an event in a blue tunic with a
white sash, the pennons fluttering, Princess Genvieve's gorgeous
costume, the courtesy and noble bearing exuded by all around -- 
the general wonder of a newbie at an event.  Four years later I hold 
a principality office, I'm a squire, and on the Princess' Escort of the 
Mists, and I've made more good friends than I can count.  My life would
be so much poorer without this experience, and I am trying now to give
back to the Society some of the good I've recieved from it.  I live 
in a kingdom heavy with peers, and I've learned the value of the energy
and enthusiasm new blood brings to the group.  

So I'll ask both  sets: the newbies and the Established People,
How can we do better by those interested in the SCA?  How can we get
across the ideas of the medieval re-creation, the ideals of chivalry,
the learning and the teaching of others?  I go to as many demos as I
can.  Partly to show off pretty armor, partly to show that women can
and do fight in the current middle ages, partly to talk about things
other than fighting that the SCA does.  Other ideas, people?

Lady Coranna of Cavan esq, OLM / Laurie Cavanaugh
