Well, since an answer to this one hasn't shown up in my mailer yet, I
guess I'll take a chance on duplicating other messages.  And I'll keep
it reasonably short, just in case.

Polling is the process whereby the Crown asks the advice of the members
of an Order, as to who should be admitted to that Order.  The Monarchs
send out a letter with the names of those gentles who have been
recommended to them as possible candidates for the Order.  (Anyone may
write to the Crown to recommend candidates.)  The Monarchs select those
gentles for which they wish to poll, and may add other names as they
see fit.  Basic information is provided about each candidate's 
accomplishments, along with the name of their home group, and sometimes
a pointer to a reliable person who is familiar with their work.  The
members of the Order vote on the candidates and send their votes and
comments to the Crown.

In the East, the following constraints apply.  I do not know how many
of these conditions are in effect in other Kingdoms:

Members of an Order have four options for casting their vote on each 
candidate:  Yes, No, Abstain or Wait.  They may also comment.

All those Orders which carry a Patent of Arms are polled for.  This
includes not only Laurel, Pelican and Chivalry but also patents for
Royal Peerages.

There are three Orders of High Merit, for fighting, service and arts &
sciences, which are polling orders.  Lady of the Rose is a polling
order.

Orders of Honor are not polling orders.  (These are lesser Kingdom
orders.  There are about four or five of them in the East.)

Candidates must be polled for before the Crown may induct them into the
Order in question.

The Crown is not required to abide by the advice of the Order.

Members of an Order who fail to return two polls in a row are dropped
from the active rolls of the Order, which only means that they won't
get another polling letter until they write and re-instate themselves.

Most Monarchs poll twice in their reign.  By law, they must poll at
least once.

Being now a member of two polling orders, in a huge kingdom, I find I
spend hours answering the letters.  Master Kobayashi, who introduced
himself here a few days ago, is a member of four polling orders (and if
the Queen's Order of Courtesy were still a polling order here, it would
be five) and he dreads the arrival of the postman when another poll is
due.  Members tend to call each other long distance to ask for more
information on candidates in far-away groups.  It's just plain work,
and one of the better arguments I can think of for keeping the size of
Kingdoms reasonably manageable.

So, which Kingdoms out there DON'T poll?  And is there anyplace besides
Atlantia where the Crown must abide by the wishes of the Order?

--Marian Greenleaf

