Subj:	RE: "Neo-Pagans"

Part of the official definition of neo-paganism is that there is no official
definition :-)

I think of neo-paganism as being a nature-based (i.e. viewing man as an element
of nature, as opposed to the subduer thereof) individual-growth-based (tran-
scendentalist) religion.  It is an umbrella that covers a lot of people who
might identify themselves as witches (as in wise {wo}men), practicians of the
lighter traditions of the occult (i.e. not satanists, who are a christian-
reaction group, and not many of the academic schools of the occult such as
demonology and alchemy--if anyones freaking out, remember I'm distinguishing
a difference not a similarity, here).

We generally celebrate the turning of the year with the quarters (solstices/
equinoxes) and cross-quarters (dates about halfway in between the quarters,
since 3 months is too long to wait for a good feast day).  Some folk also
celebrate lunar holidays (new and full moons, et al).  If you look at the
catholic calendar, you will find that a lot of the major feast days were set
on dates approximating these, partially because of the Jewish calendar, and
partially because of the churches co-opting of the holidays of the religions
of the indiginous European population.

Although many neo-pagans claim linear descent from the pre-christian religions
of Europe, I think that this is probably a yearning about as successful as
the SCA's yearning to re-create midieval society (even just the good parts!:-).
There are similar groups in most religions who try to go back to the "roots"
of say, early christianity, or pre-diaspora judaism.

Neo-pagans are well documented in "Drawing Down the Moon" (1986?, Beacon Press,
by Margot Adler), and a good intro to pagan ritual might be "The Spiral
Dance" by Starhawk (sorry, don't remember publication info).

There is at least one national pagan organization associated with a fairly
well-known religious denomination (the Covenant of Unitarian Universalist
Pagans, or CUUPs), and a smattering of other organizations, but in general, 
the neo-pagan movement is highly unorganized, and seems to like it that way.

Personally, I think of us as a bunch of free-thinkers who believe in a kinship
with nature, believe in the personally transformative power of ritual, and
agree to disagree on the details.  Religion as an expression and wellspring
of art.

						Shava/Sophia

