That was marvellously well said.  I find that much of neo-Paganism is, alas,
based on reactionary responses.  The prevailing society is discriminatory
against women, therefore the Goddess is pre-eminent to the point of
monotheism and discrimination in the opposite direction.  In many areas,
Pagans/Witches are subject to hostility; since some join the SCA as an 
escape from mundania, they may turn that hostility around.  I do sympathise
with Alfgar, since it is very difficult to be that liminal thing, a Christian
magician -- the Christians don't want him because he's a magician, and the
Pagans don't want him because he's a Christian.  A little more tolerance
all round would be the ideal, but alas, we are human.  I only recently
realised the extent of my own paranoia and insularity: I was talking to my
mother about the media's inflation of occult-related crime, prompted by
slanderous publications by the religious Right, and she said, "Look, kid, I
read all kinds of different news publications, and watch the television
news, and I can tell you, THERE IS NO MEDIA BLITZ.  We're not hearing about
it.  1000 policemen receiving a cult-crime newsletter published by 
fundamentalists is a drop in the bucket!"  And I like to think of myself as
being pretty rational!

So there we are.  I suspect that the unspoken (and sometimes spoken!) rule
against religious discussion in the SCA has done much to foster all this
misunderstanding.  Communication -- and NOT proselytising -- is the only
solution.

