I was just reminded of this by the fact that it came up on the
rec.arts.movies newsgroup.

The movie, Knightriders, is on Cinemax this month. I *think* there is
still one more showing (at 2:30 in the morning, or some similarly
godforsaken hour). If you haven't seen it before, get someone to tape
it for you; it's worth it.

As I've heard it, the movie started out as being about the SCA (I've
heard that it is *very* loosely based on an Eastern Crown Tourney a 
number of years ago). Between trying to spice it up to improve sales,
and generally make it a bit more mythic, it comes out being pretty far
from the SCA in fact, but is still in the right ballpark in spirit.
It's a cross of the early SCA, Renaissance Fairs, a dash of Arthurian
legend, and motorcycles. At least, the plot is. But the main focus of
the story is the people in the (never named) group, and most of them
are the kind of people we all know from the Society. The conflict of the
movie comes from the way that their dreams of How Things Should Be
interact.

Anyone in the Society would probably enjoy this movie (at least, I've
never encountered one who doesn't, and I've shown it to dozens), so
long as you *don't* go in with the expectation that this is the SCA.
It isn't, but it's something that the SCA could almost have been, in
a different world.

(In case you hadn't guessed, this is one of my favorite movies -- The
Lion in Winter is the other, for very different reasons.)

