Remember, as I mentioned in my last message to you, that Middle Welsh
orthography is NOT reliable.  We are talking here about people just
beginning to write in their native language, using an alphabet (the
latin) that was completely inadequate to the task.  As simple a name
as "Gwen" could appear as Guen, Gven, Gwyn, Gwynn, Gvwynn, and any
number of permutations thereof, all of them pronounced differently in
modern Welsh, but all of them signifying the same name in Middle Welsh.

I recommend A GRAMMAR OF MIDDLE WELSH, by D. Simon Evans, published by
the Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies (sorry, can't remember the date
offhand).  It will give you a very clear idea of just how confused those
poor early scribes were.

