Subject: Answering Machines and other mundanities

    
    I have heard the term golem used for answering machines; I believe
    that this has the same problem as referring to cars as dragons.
    Yes, golems and dragons are medieval concepts, but I can't imagine
    that very many people would've referred to their wagon or horse
    as a dragon, or tell you to leave a message with their golem!  I've
    done it too, but I think it's part of what makes SCA events seem
    more like cocktail parties in garb than medieval tourneys or revels.
    
    Wagon or wain works well for a car; valet, manservant, or butler for 
    an answering machine.  For similar reasons, I prefer tax collector or
    check in table over troll (neither of these alternatives is great, but
    they're better than troll), and privy over porta-castle or shrine to
    St. John of the stagnant waters, both of which are rather tacky. 
    
    I'm not trying to be holier-than-anybody.  I've used the
    mundane/fantasy euphemisms for most of my 8 years in the SCA.  I'd
    like to see a friendly group effort to get away from them though,
    in the hope that we can recapture a bit of the magic that seems to
    be slipping away.
    
