Given that the rules of the lists specifically forbid any religious
display in the lists, the College of Arms is basically forced to take
a very conservative view of what is permitted in armory.  As someone
else pointed out, religious symbolism in heraldry is very much period
practice, and such things as crosses and the like are so common as to
be ignorable.  On the other hand, we will not register armory with a
crucifix, or the Hand of God, or any other excessively religious
display.

As far as the lady Sophia's question about the use of "fidelis", that
doesn't present a problem since period style heraldry did not use
wording or other such abstract symbols (i.e., numbers, astrological
symbols, etc), so we don't register that at all.

Personally, I think the SCA devoid of religion would be a poorer
place.  I am not religious in any regard myself, but I see religion,
properly and tastefully used, as an important element of medieval
life.  I am one of the great proponents of the veneration of St Pyr
(Drink deeply to St Pyr!) in and around Rusted Woodlands, and I
delight in such things as...

-- Duke Cariadoc's use of proper Islamic greetings.

-- Master Vasili's annual Old Church Slavonic mass at the War

-- The annual pagan circle at the War

In short, I like any persona done well.  As Lady Deonora pointed out
so well, the key is tolerance and forbearance.


