bad name and were strongly resented both by the pagans and the Christians
(whose moral indignation knew no bounds).  Fortunately, the worst of
the offending oo-oo's moved FAR out barony, and the oo-oo household also
lost members and became less active, so it settled back down to quietude.

For the most part, no one will ever complain about comments or practices
religious unless they are made offensively OR are absolutely out of period.
I, for instance, autocrated an event that was on a religious theme, The Feast
of the Translation of the Holy Blessed Virgin Martyz St. Elena.  Now, St.
Elena was a local of surpassing skill as cook and needleworker, who had been
forced by mundane circumstances to move into no-man's land outside the barony's
borders.  It happend that our Chronicler, a good friend of this lady, was
given to writting whimsical pieces for the SALAMANDER about various people
in the barony and he postulated, in one issue, that Elena, having moved
away from all her friends and having a tendency to forget to eat for 2 or 3
days at a time, had probably forgotten to eat and was now dead, a martyr.
Well, this caught on, and soon people were referring to her as St. Elena and
attributing miracles to her.  A "cult" of St. Elena began to grow, complete
with hagiography.  I thought it would be lots of fun to do a St. Elena event,
complete with the saint herself, so I started doing some research.  It turned
out that in period, when a saint's relics were moved from one location to
another, the day was declared a feast day, called the Feast of the Translations
of St. _____.  So, I figured, we'd "translate" St. Elena's relics back to 
Bhakail.

The event included a solemn procession, headed by the Vicar of House
Ridgefield (in his ecclesiastical robes), followed by several of the
"relics" of the saint -- the holy, wonder-working egg whip, which had 
been known to beat the demons out of a curdled bernaise sauce, and the
miraculous lemon faucet, which, when stuck into a lemon, would cause
juice to flow unendingly.  And the, the incredibly life-life effigy of
the saint was carried in by 6 processing monks, all in black robes, singing
Gaudete with new words detailing the miracles of the saint's life.  The Vicar
then gave a brief sermon on the life of the saint, after which the 
incredibly life-lie effigy sprang up from it's resting place and a new
miracle was declared, after which we all went downstairs and ate an
enormous feast.

Now, only one (rather priggish) Christian was offended by the concept
of this event, and she stayed away.  Neither pagans or Christians in
attendence were offended by the whole idea, and everyone had a good time.

That's the way religion SHOULD be handled in the SCA -- without everyone
getting their nose out of joint as soon as somone of another persuasion
mentions their religious preferences.

Tolerance.  Tolerance is the key to courtesy on this subject within the
Society.

Deo

PS:  Mustapha -- I applaud your comments and we DO appreciate what you're
doing, persona-wise.  You are a shining example of what people CAN do
with their personas...


