Good Gentles:
	I have listened with great interest to the converse on religion in our
society, and wish to address some of the issues raised, and one but little
seen.

	First: I am Diego Mundoz, was born in northern Castile in 1099, and
have for the last decade resided in the Eastern Barony of Carolingia. While 
back in Castile I lived at Court, waiting while my clain to the family holding
is resolved.

	When I was introduced to the customs of the society the concern for
religion part of my very first "novice lecture", and it was explained thus:
here and now, whatever our origins, we all start equal, and rise or stagnate by
our own efforts. To invoke a supernatural power to in any aspect retard the
efforts of another, on the field, in Court, or at any endeavor, would be a most
serious offense against Honor and Courtesy. There would be no offense in
wearing the accepted public symbol of one's faith, though if asked to do so on
the field it was to be removed or placed out of sight. The cross (and other
simialr symbols) were acceptable in heraldry (subject to period usage), as
they were to pervasive to ignore.
	This was not to discourage or malign the belief of the persona, or the
mundane person, but rather to kill at birth any potential for religious
conflict.

	The question at hand is how to reconcile this policy with those
personas for whom religion is an integral and visible part of daily life.
Religious tension of one kind or another touched the homeland of every Society
member at some time in period. Europeans, especially, have likely either
witnessed it or heard of it first-hand. Not to be aware to the issues, even if
you have no immediate difficulty, I hold betrays an ignorance of mediaval life.


	I perceive, unfortunately, very few solid options. I count myself one
of the fortunate. Back in Castile conditions were such that to whom one owed
service was much more important than to whom one prayed. I am told that this is
also the case in many of the lands far to the East. Theological differences are
dismissed in the face of something much more fun: politics!
	For the rest I know no simple answer, and seek counsel thereon. The
only general idea I have had: after a decade in this Barony I consider myself
both a resident and a guest. As a resident it is my right to believe as I
choose, though expression of thos beliefs may be limited. As a guest I am bound
not to cause unnecessary distress to other residents and guests, as certain
expressions of my faith surely might.

	I should like to engage in a discussion of this matter with concerned
gentles, with two goals. First, to more clearly understand the law and custom
of the Society, and second, to improve the instruction of novices.

						Yours in Service,

						Diego Mundoz,
							Carolingia

