Subject: Divine names & their use in the SCA
Reply-To: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu


Some divine names certainly became common human given names in period,
often by way of becoming Saint's names.  Examples of these include
Rhiannon, Brighid (Bridget), Myrddin, Aidan.  In general, however, the
association of devine names with the gods, or at least with evil and
un-Christian demons died very slowly, and the Church was in no hurry
to encourage people to use these names.  Rather, they encourage the
adoption of the pan-European name stock, mostly Roman derived & saint
names, or, as in ireland, spread the name stock of the conquering
Normans into new lands.

In fact, there is no evidence that Bran or Dylan was ever used as a
given name in period.  There is one reference that I know to a
"Dillon" in period Wales, but note that in Welsh that is a very
different-sounding name.  

Since many people in the Society take the things very seriously, as
recent discussions about paganism on this net will attest, and since
it is a general policy of the College of Arms that no name should
imply that the individual is of other than earthly human descent, the
policy on divine names is that they may be used only if specifically
shown to have been used in period.  This may be a touch
over-conservative, but it does strike a reasonable and objective
balance: if you can prove it was used in period, then it's OK;
otherwise, no.  The same standard would apply to names of dwarves or
giants from Welsh or Norse mythology, names of monsters and heros from
Greek mythology, and indeed to names taken from Tolkein and other
fantasy worlds.  As long as the bearer of the name is human, and the
individual in question is not so famous & unique as to present other
problems, the name should be accepted.

One last note: I don't know if the use of "Jesus" can be shown in
period.  I'd be interested to see a citation, though I'll be surprised
if one exists.

