primary purpose of the society is to be educational, and that anything that
is done at events, should have that spirit in mind.  It is important to
keep in mind that while it is acceptable for your persona, or you, to have
strong religeous feelings, it is not acceptable for you to impose them on
others.  This is a very 20th century standard, but it has helped keep
religeous struggles out of our national politics for the last 100 years, and
religeous persecution is one period phenomenon, which along with period hygene
practices, which we as a society should choose *not* to recreate.  
Thus I normally avoid the "correct" greeting of a Muslim to a 
unbeliever ("May Allah guide you to the right path") in favour of the more
courteous "May Allah give you Peace", which is correctly used only for
Mulsims.  (I use it in this letter as a sincere wish for wisdom for us all
in this most delicate matter.)

I myself have run afoul of the prohabition against religeous usages on the
field.  I had chosen for myself the frase "al-Ghalaba `ain al-Haqqi" 
(Victory from Truth)                                          -
as a motto, and had designed a lovely version of it to be placed on my 
buckler.  Persona reasons prohibit me from using most pictorial devices. I,
later discovered that al-Haqqi could also be translated as God (being one of
his nine and ninety most beautiful names), I have not had time to re-design
the caligraphy, or repaint my buckler.  I currently handle the problem by 
informing my opponent as to what is written on the buckler and asking his
permission to use it, before entering the lists with it.

I think the key to the situation is following your concience, and exercising
your tact.  The neo-pagan groups are subjected to considerable hostility and
paranoia outside the SCA, yet inside the SCA, where for the most part, we take
care to follow the guidelines I have discussed, they are free from those 
influences.  Thus they react more strongly when the freedom that they so
seldom get is threatened.  Of course, the answer is always that no amount
of rules or guidelines will take the place of common sense (a rare and
precious commodity).  I beg you all to remember that we are all brothers
and sisters in the Society, striving to recreate a common world, even if
we are not brothers and sisters in religeon.

May Allah, the Generous, the Merciful grant you all Peace.

	--Mussttapha
	

