Subject: Newbie Situation, for both old and new

Greetings!

First, let me introduce myself.

My name is Tatyana d'Aquitaine and I attend college in Carolingia.
(Felding, mundanely: Wellesley College). I am a twelfth century merchant's 
daughter. My interests include dancing, mumming (acting) and fencing. 

Secondly, I would like to address the problem of the college student/newbie 
situation in Carolingia, and how to work around cliquishness.

I disagee with Justin's analysis of the newbie situation, but one must 
understand that we come from different viewpoints. Justin is a more-
established, mid-twenties type person, whereas I am a less-established
college student.

I believe that Carolingia is divided into two parts: the well-established
older members and the college students (primarily from 3 area colleges: 
Wellesley, Brandeis, and Harvard). Most of the new members to the SCA come
through the colleges, becoming more accepted after graduation if they stay
in the area. Very few people join through any other route.
This sets up a split in the barony between the "old guard" who all know
each other and the college students who all know each other. I think
that the "old guard" is a bit overwhelmed by all of the college students, 
especially with the influx at the beginning of the school year.
The main problem is a lack of communication between the two groups. 
Therefore, most of the college students hang around together feeling like
they don't belong to the group as a whole. The older members perhaps feel a 
little uneasy around all the college students.

Communication, I think, is the root of the problem. Perhaps this is what is 
occuring in other areas as well. 

To solve this situation and cliquishness in general, it is important to let
the people around you know that you are truly interested in the SCA.  Once you
seperate yourself from the general crowd by talking to the older members,
there is a greater level of communication, solving the problem of feeling
like you don't belong.
Therefore, I think that newish people should talk with others. Display your 
friendliness and encourage your friends to join with the same attitude.

I think that the more-established members should follow Lady Siobhan's advice
about remembering how you felt as a newbie.  Try to seek out new people and
introduce yourself!  Baron Patri du Chat Gris of Carolingia has adopted a 
policy of during court asking new members to stand up and he welcomes them.
This has worked very well.

Sorry if I have offended anyone with my ramblings,

Farewell,
Tatyana

PS. A fellow Felding has asked that I include these statements: 

1. The college group is an advantage to a new member because she is provided 
with a group of people like herself who are concerned about her. Perhaps this
is why people tend to stick to the SCA when in a borough (college group).

2. The communication problem is self-perpetuating because cliques form 
naturally among the college students because we live together and all know 
each other.  












