Subject: Powers of the Crown
Message-Id: <579392370/kee@NL.CS.CMU.EDU>

I agree with Arval; the Eastern Crown really does have a fair amount of
power.  But then so do the other parts of the system, as he outlined
them.  I think Justin is right in implying that the system works even
when the King chooses not to do very much, but I have to disagree about
the "figurehead" business!  Arval and I are both Great Officers of the
East at this point (I having just been invested with Arts and Sciences)
and thus we are rather acutely aware of how much power the Crown can
wield.  

An interesting sidelight is that in the principality of Drachenwald, Curia
must actually APPROVE laws in order for them to take effect; this is
largely because with such a transient population, the stability
afforded by Curia must be emphasized.  But in the East as a whole, the
Crown only has to CONSULT Curia.   In Atlantia, which used to be a
principality of the East, the Polling Orders must APPROVE candidates before 
the Crown can bestow the Order in question.  In the East, the Crown
only has to CONSULT the Order.  As Arval pointed out, however, when the
Crown defies the wishes of an Order, the recipient of the award may
find that the disapproval of the other members weighs heavily upon him
or her.  Generally, there's an informal rule in the East that the Crown
may piss off one order per reign without tremendous adverse
consequences.  Some Monarchs just plow on through and do what they like
in that regard, and eventually the dust tends to settle and the new
members become accepted, except in some extreme cases.  (The Chivalry
seem to have particularly long memories, however.)

We don't bow or kneel to empty thrones, and even when I was a
Midrealmer, I found that to be too much for me to practice personally.

The degree of involvement of the King in the battles at Pennsic tends
to vary greatly with the ability of the King in question.  I think this
is as it should be.  We have a Crown-Appointed Warlord, and a wise King
will appoint a good strategist with whom he is comfortable, who also
has wide support in the Kingdom as a whole.  Sometimes the Warlord is
him/herself a past monarch, as in the case of Duke Siegfried.

Somehow I am not surprised that a view of the King as figurehead should
have come out of Carolingia (and this is NOT a dig at Carolingia; I like
the place a lot.)  Carolingia has a long tradition of independence, as
it were.  But I really have to disagree.  It's true that if the Crown
vanished tomorrow, Carolingia would go on as it always has (and so
would Debateable Lands, for that matter!), but on the larger scale of
the Kingdom as a whole, things would certainly change.

I really think that the tradition of a fair amount of independence for
local groups and territorial Barons is a positive thing in the East,
and makes us very strong in our diversity.  The Crown, ideally, is one
of the main things that draws us together and helps us retain some
common identity.  I guess sometimes this could look as though it were a
position which is just for show.  But I know from experience that this
is not really the case.  There is a level of activity at which the
Crown is quite important, including appointments for certain offices,
making members of Orders, and structuring Kingdom law.  Most such
things affect us all sooner (like changes to Law) or later (changing
the makeup of an Order in such as way as to gradually alter its character.)

There's no question that in the East we pay less attention to the
outward regalia than is done in many other Kingdoms.  This is gradually
changing.  However, we DO like the Monarchs to "be good in Court";
all the trappings in the world can't make up for an uninspiring
performance on the throne.  We can become very fond of those who do a
good job in this regard, to the point of ignoring their foibles in a
way that might have been quite unlikely during a previous reign.

I suspect that the sheer size of the East also has a lot to do with our
governing traditions.  Anybody care to discuss it?

I've gone on long enough!

