I think that sometimes using a different variant of one's name than
that passed by the heralds is justified.  (Note I said "sometimes".)
For instance, my own lord is registered as "Maghnus an Cnoic na n'Iora" 
(or something close to that.)  It means "Manos of the Hill of
Squirrels" in Irish Gaelic.  However, being an Irish name, its spelling
was not well-associated with the pronunciation, and for years he would
show up on polling letters only to draw dozens of abstentions because
nobody knew who that name belonged to.  (Eventually the story became
enough of a joke that people figured out whose name that was by hearing
the story told, and he now has two Kingdom orders. ;-)  Aside from being
hard to recognize, the name was awkward to pronounce and remember, and
on taking a couple of Irish dictionaries to it, we found that we
couldn't translate it to our satisfaction--but this would be
understandable if the heralds had rendered it in medieval Irish.
Meanwhile, every time my lord entered a list away from home, he would
have to listen very carefully to hear his name called, as nobody would
ever say it the same way twice.  But he likes "Manos", and the "Hill of
Squirrels" idea, so he never tried to change the name.

A couple of years ago, he made friends with a native speaker of Irish.
Eventually the SCA came up, and "Manos" asked for advice about his name.
The native speaker suggested "Manos de Cnoc an Iora" as the form which
sounded most natural to him.

Now, we don't know if the name which was actually passed was drawn from
medieval or modern Irish.  We do know that it was modified a fair
amount by the heralds, from the original submission.  Currently, with
the help of a friend in Atlantia who is doing research on early-period
Irish names, we are trying to establish what the early spelling for it
would have been (say, seventh century or so.)  Already it appears the
the spelling "Manos" is one of the preferred changes!  That would be a
nice thing to have happen.

Meanwhile, my lord uses the form "Magnus de Cnoc an Iora".  I don't
blame him.  It's not what the heralds passed, but it sure is easier to
pronounce and remember, and it means the same thing.  All his scrolls
and polling letters use the "official" version of the name, which
is fine with him.   I suppose we will have learned enough eventually to
re-submit the name in a documented early-period form.  (Anybody out there 
who does this kind of thing, by the way, is welcome to send me mail!)

As things stand, the modified version of the name, which he actually
uses, won't conflict with anyone else, because it is so close to the
orginal version.  And it isn't offensive.  And it is a name which might
have been used in period.  So, I don't see anything wrong with using it.

