Received: from sabbath.rutgers.edu (TCP 20001406433) by AI.AI.MIT.EDU 11 May 88 14:10:26 EDT
Received: by sabbath.rutgers.edu (5.54/1.15) 
	id AA01645; Wed, 11 May 88 14:12:48 EDT
Date: Wed, 11 May 88 14:12:48 EDT
From: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu (Joshua Mittleman)
Message-Id: <8805111812.AA01645@sabbath.rutgers.edu>
To: SCA@ai.ai.mit.edu
Subject: Names, Heralds, & Offensiveness
Reply-To: joshua@paul.rutgers.edu


The following letter was part of a discussion of the return of a name
and device by Laurel a month ago.  The name submitted was "Jean
d'Eaux", the device "Argent, upon a tombstone sable, a fountain".  The
tombstone which was drawn in the typical "Boot-Hill" shape, a
rectangle with a half-circle on top.  Later research showed that this
shape of tombstone is probably not period.  No conflicts were found
for either name or device.  The submission was returned for reasons
which are given below.  With the submitter's permission, I am posting
this letter to the net to address certain issues of what the heralds
do, why we do it, and why we ought to do it.  Replies & discussion are
encouraged.  

	Your Servant,

		Arval, Brigantia.

=========================

I am happy to discuss the return of your name, but I must ask that you
not take any of these comments as personal attack.  Some of this
discussion is rather blunt, but is meant to explain, not to criticize.
Please forgive anything that may seem overly abrupt.

To expand: Your name was not really returned for any single reason;
rather, it was felt that the many different problems added up to
reason for return.  To list:

- the name is obviously intended as a joke.  It is generally the
policy of the College of Arms not to register joke names, because such
names are not consistent with period practice.  In this case
especially, it was felt that the joke was inappropriate because it
would be so instantly recognizable as such, and therefore that many
SCA members would find it inappropriate and disturbing.

- The name is not consistent with period French naming practice.  It
is grammatically incorrect, since the correct French for "of the
Waters" is "des Eaux".  The construction you use actually implies that
"Eaux" is a French placename, but that name is not properly
constructed for a French placename.

- Whether you recognized it or not, the name DOES have a scatalogical
reference which was immediately evident to nearly every herald outside
the East Kingdom who reviewed your submission.  Indeed, I happen to
know that several heralds in the College of Arms conducted straw polls
among their local groups, the result of which was strong evidence that
most SCAdians would consider the name inappropriate as a medieval
name.  When  combined with the visual effect of your device, the
scatalogical reference was deemed overly offensive.

- The name is so similar in pronuncation to "John Doe" as to be
indistinguishable by anyone who has not already seen the spelling.
SCA names are meant to be real names, names that could have existed in
our period.  Your name does not meet that standard in any regard.

A little general philosophy:

One of the jobs of the College of Arms is to prevent the use of names
which a significant proportion of the membership of the society would
find offensive.  This is not an easy task, and generally difficult to
decide.  Our approach is usually to err on the side of caution, and, I
am afraid to admit, on the side of paranoia.  It too often happens
that someone submits a name or device "to get one by the heralds"; one
begins to get a touch over-sensitive.  While I believe that you were
not trying to hide anything, and indeed, I said as much to the College
of Arms, the problems remain.

The definition of "offensive" is always somewhat nebulous, and rightly
so: things change, and we certainly don't want to be locked into any
one rigid set of specifications.  The flip side of this flexibility is
that there is often not a clear-cut case one way or the other.  In the
current case, I felt that "Jean d'Eaux" would be an acceptable, if
slightly silly name.  We have in the past accepted things like "Miles
Long", because although there is a joke in the name, it is also a
correctly formed period name.  In the current case, as explained
above, that last isn't true.

Names deemed offensive fall into several categories (my own analysis):

1) Names which disturb the atmosphere of the SCA: Names which, though
in period themselves, have such strong out-of-period references as to
offend many members.  Most joke names fall into this category: Jules
of the Nile, for example, is a really good period name.  We would not
register it.  "Jean d'Eaux" falls into this category, because although
the legal fiction John Doe is actually a period phenomenon, the
associations with that name for most people are decidedly modern.   One
of the reasons for the return of this name was the common euphemism
for porto-Johns, "Cathedrals of St. John of the Waters".  When
combined with the visual scatalogy of the device, this reference was
deemed offensive.

2) Names which imply non-human birth.  These are the most common cases
of offensiveness returns.  Probably because of the scarcity of
information about names in many early period cultures, many SCAdians
choose & try to register names of gods or other superhuman beings.  We
get more Myrddin's, Bran's, Dylan's, and Rhiannon's than all other
Welsh names combined.
   A divine or non-human name may only be used if there is reasonable
evidence for its use as a human name in period.  Thus, Myrddin,
Gwalchmai, Hercule, and the like are acceptable, though discouraged,
because they can be shown to have been used by people in period.  I
should point out that in the period when these beings were seen as
gods, NO ONE would have been so foolish as to name his child after a
god.  There is a limit, however, even on these names: there may be no
other reference to the super-human being in either name or device.
Thus, you can call yourself Myrddin the Fisherman, but you cannot call
yourself Myrrddin of the Flames or Myrddin ap Don.  Similarly,
Rhiannon ferch Rhys is an acceptable name, but Rhiannon Horsewoman is
not.  Other names, Grendel, Zeus, Odin, Gwydion, etc.  may never be
used in an SCA name, because they were used in period only for the
non-human in question.

3) Scatalogical, sexist, politically, or otherwise blatantly offensive
names:  Wilhelm Hitler, Peter Nunraper, George Ferret-flattener, for
example.  I don't think this needs any explanation.
4) Pretentious Names: No name should imply noble or other rank.  Thus,
given names such as "Earl", or "Rex" may not be used.  Similarly, no
Scottish surname of the form "<clan name> of <placename>" may be
registered if the actual clan had/has its seat at that place.  In
Scotland, a surname such as "MacLeod of Dunvegan" is in fact a legal
title reserved to the chieftain of the clan.  Another example: the
name of a significant place may not be combined with the given name of
any noble who ruled it.  Thus, although there may have been thousands
of John's living in London, the name "John of London" is not
acceptable, since that style was used by King John of England.  In
general, the name of any capital seat of a Duchy, Kingdom, County,
etc. should not be combined with the name of any noble who ruled
there.  Generally (although not always) the addition of a surname
unrelated to the ruling family is sufficient difference.  Thus, while
you could not call yourself William of Warwick, you could call
yourself William Fletcher of Warwick.  However, note that this is not
always sufficient: it depends on the importance of the individual with
whom the name conflicts.

There might be other categories that I've missed, but this covers the
most important ones.

On the question of how to revise your name for re-submission: My first
advice to you is to re-think why you chose the name, what you really
want a name to do for you, and what you really think the SCA is about.
Do you really want, someday, to be called into Court to be given your
peerage, and be announced to the world as "Sir John Doe"?  To put it
another way, do you really see your place in the Society as a joke?  I
apologize for the bluntness of these statements, but I really believe
that you are making a mistake, and doing a disservice to yourself that
you may long regret.  I urge you to think about this for a while
before you commit yourself one way or the other.

I should also point out that registering one name & using another is a
very bad idea.  First of all, it will cause you endless problems,
since on any official document (scrolls, for example), your official
name would be used.  You would also gain the dislike of many members
of the SCA (not just heralds, by the way).  In my own opinion, one
shared by many, such conduct is at best impolite, since it states that
you have deliberately chosen to ignore the rules of the Society, and
have chosen to offend members of the Society.  At worst, it is
dishonorable.  How would you feel if you were confronted by someone at
a feast who insisted on smoking in the Hall, drinking beer out of
aluminum cans, and wearing his Hawiian shorts, and when told that
this conduct was forbidden by Kingdom law and by the customs of the
