The development of clique in local branches is a probably faced by any
organization, and the SCA is no exception.  I think every large group
has had experiences with one or another circle of friends trying to
monopolize the running of the group.  For what its worth, the best
thing to do is keep on trying.  If you show that you have alot to
offer, that you will not give in to petty social politics, then you
will eventually be accepted.  Alternatively, you can always take upon
yourself the recruiting of new memebers.  Hold sewing workshops, or
heraldry classes, or fighting practices at your place, and invite the
whole shire.  

I've also found that when cliquishness sets in, the cliquers tend not
to travel alot.  The result is usually that most other groups forget
they exist, or at least don't care.  So, if you start travelling to
neighboring groups, and telling people who you are and where you're
from, you will immediately discover that they are quite happy to see
your group active again.  Once you make contacts outside your group,
you'll be surprised how quickly you become invaluable to your own
group.


