Lord Justin du Coeur writes:

> Yes, the power of the royalty alters *radically* as you move East. The
> King here is largely a figurehead, unless he actively decides otherwise.
> The King must be, first and foremost, good in court; several, such as
> Sebastian Nightwind and Siegfried, stand out as particularly good examples
> of this. If the King is good at strategy (or thinks that he is), he will
> usually direct the battles at Pennsic, but is generally not a spearhead
> in the actual fighting.

I think you are over-stating the restrictions on the Crown here in the
East.  Indeed. in law, the King of the East has much less power than,
for example, the King of the West.  However, remember how short the
Eastern book of law is.  Most of the "law" of the East isn't even
written down...it exists only as custom.  (This, by the way, I
consider to be both vert period & very beneficial)  A recent incident
may make the point: Hanno ruled as King of the East several years ago,
and as King of Caid last year.  In Caid, the King's word is law.
However, it was his strong impression that he had much more real power
in the East, because if Caidans didn't like what he decreed, they just
ignore it and him.  (No offense intended to Caid)

The balance of power in the East is an interesting one.  The Crown is
restricted in certain important ways: no law may be made without
consulting Curia, and the high awards (peerages & kingdom orders of
merit) may not be given without consulting the order.  Note the use of
the word "consult".  After holding Curia or writing to the Orders, the
King may freely ignore their advice.  He doesn't even have to read the
responses to His polling letters; he just has to ask for them.  The
result of this structure is an interesting three-way balance of power:
The Crown, the Officers of States, and the Great Orders of the
Kingdom.  On one hand, only the Crown may decree any law or present
any award.  The other bodies have only advisory power in these
regards.  However, the Crown passes on in six months.  Officers sit
for two years or more, and generally have influence on the choice of
thier successors.  Polling Orders are forever.  A King who acts
without the consent of the Orders, or against the strong wishes of His
officers is going to be in for deep grief thereafter.  A typical
example, stripped of names: a King of the East knighted a lord against
the strong wishes of the Chivalry.  The results has been that he and
his squires have effectively been ostracized by the Chivalry.  Such
incidents are usually unpleasant, and so unfortunate.  A wise King
avoids them.

I'll admit that when laid out this way, it all looks rather nebulous
and seriously catty.  In practice though, it works remarkably well.


