Which isn't the same thing as saying that it is beyond discussion, or even that
it was well-considered.  The prohibition, for example, extends to scouting --
although scouting was developed, in part, as an activity for minors.

The mundane legal situation is cloudy.  My understanding is that in New York,
for example, if someone under eighteen is hurt by someone over eighteen, the
fact that it was all in fun and that it was an accident and that, anyway, the
minor signed a waver and had a note from his mother carries very little weight
in court.  In Pennsylvania the law is much fuzzier:  the impression I got was
that the only way to really find out is to get sued and see what happens.

There's a certain logic to not taking chances with the well-being of minors.
There's also a certain logic in not taking chances with the legal exposure of
the society.  It is, however, possible to carry the latter goal to extremes.  I
have been in the SCA for less than two years, and I feel safe in saying that
the amount of paperwork which the society demands from individuals and groups
(I didn't have exposure to the higher levels of the bureaucracy) has more than
doubled in that time.

