Subject: Bringing in the next generation

I hadn't realized that the problem of driving off new people was so common.
Basically, the only thing that can be done about it is for *you* to try to
change it. The problem hasn't been too bad in Carolingia, because there are
a *lot* of different groups that one can get involved in, and few of them
are cliques. But the smaller the group, the more acute the problem can 
become. And even in a fairly open group, it's easy for a new person to
feel lost. Even if no one is being conciously cliquish, it can appear that
way from the outside if people aren't actively *trying* to approach the
new people. This applies to experienced SCAdians from outside, every bit
as much as novices.

If you really care about the situation, work at it. When you see someone
looking lost at an event, talk to them and help them out. If you *really*
feel strongly about it, volunteer for the local "out-reach" post (the post's
name varies a fair amount). But don't expect it to be easy; the "out-reach"
post is one of the very hardest, particularly if the local group doesn't
support you. It's one of those cases where the job is its own reward.

And remember one painful fact of life; some people *like* to be in a clique,
and there isn't necessarily anything wrong with that. The way to deal with it
is to bring people into it yourself. It takes a fair amount of work, but it's
the only way to make it stop being a clique.

							-- Justin du Coeur

