Subject: The power of the royalty

Yes, the power of the royalty alters *radically* as you move East. The
King here is largely a figurehead, unless he actively decides otherwise.
The King must be, first and foremost, good in court; several, such as
Sebastian Nightwind and Siegfried, stand out as particularly good examples
of this. If the King is good at strategy (or thinks that he is), he will
usually direct the battles at Pennsic, but is generally not a spearhead
in the actual fighting.

The differences between the coasts were rather dramatically underlined
when Ronald, a former King of one of the West Coast Kingdoms, became
King of the East a few years ago. All told, he didn't do badly, but there
was a great deal of friction, as the King tried to assume functions that
are normally those of the bureaucracy, and simply assumed that he had
more power to order people about than an Eastern King normally does.
People dealt with it pretty well, but there was a definite feeling of
"things are back to normal" when he stepped down.

