Sorry, I had assumed that the BOD attitude towards press conferences
was well known, but it has been a while since they stated it. Basically,
around Pennsic time several years back, there was a write-up of the SCA
in column 4 of the Wall Street Journal (ie, on the front page). It was
a basically favorable ariticle, but the entire thing had been done without
the BOD's knowledge, and that made the Board *very* nervous. Thus, they
set down an official policy that, before speaking to the press (at least,
on a national level), you should check with higher-ups. Thus, if the
Barony of Carolingia wanted to go on national TV for a blurb, they would
check with the Seneschal of the East, who would clear it with the
Steward. This isn't really to prevent people from saying things in public,
it's just so the BOD has some idea of what's going on.

This is only for fairly large-scale press, mind. No one cares about article
in college newspapers, or even medium-sized local papers. Just give some
warning before doing anything big.

