May Allah, the All-Hearing, and All-wise, bless any and all who here
this message.

Topic: Introduction

Please allow me to introduce myself, my name is Mussttapha 'ibn
as-Saqaat al-Muhaddith (Mustapha, son of the water-carrier, the
storyteller).  I am a 7th century (A.H., 13th in your Frankish years)
Arab, who is currently living in Carrolingia.  My interests include
Storytelling, Fencing, Persona and all things Arabic, I am also starting on
some of the copious research necessary to becoming a Herald

I would like to take the liberty of addressing you on three topics, my
persona, storytelling, and the level of noise comming over the net.  I
will separate the three topics with lines, so that you can easily skip
the ones you wish to ignore.

-------------------------------------------------------------------

Topic: Persona


I would like to thank Justin de Cour for his summary of persona in our
Barony, however, he omitted me, which is just as well, as it will
allow me to make my own introduction.

I became interested in an Arabic persona through two sources, my
facination with the Dervishes (Sufi's) and their tales, and my
interest in the Tales of the Arabian Nights.  Thus I chose the name of
Mussttapha, and learned how to tie a turband on my head.

Carrolingia was good about accepting my "non-standard" persona, for
two reasons.  First, although Arabs where an exotic people to those living in
the middle ages, they were not entirely unknown; many Franj, through
the crusades had visited Syria, Persia, and Turkistan, while there
where some Arab traders in Spain, Sicilly and Italy.  Second, and
perhaps more importantly, Duke Carriadoc of the Bow was a friend and
frequent visitor to the Barony, and through people were already
familiar with the concepts and customs of an Islamic persona.  This of
course does not mention that both our Seneshal and our chief Chirogean
were already established as Oriental persona.

One thing I find interesting about being a "non-standard" persona is
the level of respect I get for relatively trivial matters.  For
example, simply saying "Peace be upon you", a simple translation of
Salaam, instead of "Greetings, milord" gets me credit for `doing'
persona.  The second address is of course perfectly proper for a Saxon
or Norman persona, yet because it is almost standard scadian, people
forget it is part of a proper persona.  

I can only encourage people to pay attention to proper persona,
espeically the ethnic differences which will make people notice where
you are from.  Saying "I'm an Arab" is not as much fun as wearing a
turband and saying "Salaam" and letting people figure out that you are
an Arab.  My best sources have been tales recorded in period (in
particular the Thousand Nights and a Night), espeically those with
good footnotes.  These have given me an indication of what people
thought was proper (if perhaps a bit florid for the tales) behavior of
the time.  At any rate it is these little things that help add to the
"suspension of disbelief" which allows the current middle ages to
become real.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Topic: Storytelling

As I mentioned before, I am interesting in both preserving the oral
tradition of generations past, and maintinging the oral tradition of
this our current generation.  That is in story telling.  Currently I
and many others (including Justin who has already introduced himself)
have created a storytelling practice group.  We are currently debating
the relative merits of becoming a Guild.  Perhaps I will have a chance
to discuss the matter at some length later.

As one of my purposes is to preserve stories of the current Middle
Ages, I would like to collect some of them over the net.  In order to
keep the net from being flooded with stories, please send them to me 
"almond@hustat.harvard.edu" I will collect them and post them to the
net about once a week (or less often if I get fewer submissions).  
I am also interested in sources for period stories, those you can
could either post directly to the net, or send to me, and I will post
an updated list.  If I collect enough stories, I will typeset them,
and distribute them (for copying cost) at the Pensic War, or over the
net by request.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Topic: Net Noise

I appologies for making more noise about net organisation, but it
seems to me to be important.  The trafic on the net is high, and
making it a news group will only help those who read the news (for
example I seem to have missed the letter to new members which was put
over the net, I would have liked to see it).  To help aid those of us
who must sort through much mail, I would like to provide the following
suggestion for how to deal with the mail.

The key is to use a good subject heading.  I suggest "SCA:" followed
by a list of one word descriptions describing topics in the letter,
for example:

  Introduction -- a persona introducing himself on the net
  Persona -- discussions about personas
  Heraldry, Dance, Storytelling, Fighting, Fencing -- these are pretty
self explanatory.

These are only matters of simple courtesy, because, for example, I
enjoy dancing, but would rather not need to read volumes of mail on
how various dances are done around the known world.  I would prefer to
instead take comfort in the fact that my dancemaster (Justin) is
reading them, and will digest and relate to me the results of his
research.  

The sinlge worst type of mail is mail about how to run the net,
comments about orginization are a nuisance at best (this one
included).  And letters telling Danulf he should not discontinue the
Mailing List (a idea I heartily agree with) should be sent to
"sca-request", and not the whole mailing list.  If you must bring up
these matters with the entire list, I would like to modestly suggest
the following topic name "Net Noise".

---------------------------------------------------

Thank you for listening to my humble suggestions and comments.
Inshallah, we shall enjoy profitable discourse over the ether.

Your Obedient Servant,

	--Mustapha  al-Muhaddith
