Basically, the BoD wants to have some control (or at least
notification) about SCa members making statements to the press.  After
a few bad incidents with the SCA either accidentally or deliberately
getting bad press, they are a bit wary about the effects this may have
on our social & legal standing.  The group is big enough now that we
need to be careful about people bad mouthing us.  If one schmuck blabs
off to some gossip rag, and gives the impression that he is speaking
officially, we could be royally scrod in all sorts of ways.  So, the
BoD at least wants to know what we are doing officially.  Just to give
an example of one problem which did arise, a SCA member once wrote an
article for a teenage girls' magazine, on what it's like to be a
Princess.  She gave the BoD's address to contact for information, but
didn't mention that inquiries should include a full-sized SASE.  As a
result, the corporate office was deluged with tiny pink envelopes
requesting details, and feeling obliged to answer, they were put to a
rather large expense.  This was a minor problem, but it does
illustrate the value of a publicity corrdinator.


