Subject: personae and introductory note

I'd been interested in the "personae makeup" of various kingdoms, and
in hopes of encouraging this, I'll put in a bit about the West.
There is a great variety in personae, and the less common, such as the
Oriental folk, are not discouraged.  I would say that the majority of
the West (guesstimate 60 to 70 percent) adopts a crusader persona, or 
at least dresses that way.  I know many people, however, that will 
see some neat fabric or trim and create a costume that is completely
different from what their 'persona' usually wears.  A strong trend of
late is toward Persian or middle eastern garb (it's very cool for 
summer tourneys), but many of these folk maintain European names.  

Another interesting geographical difference, that Lady Siobhann
mentioned in the Introductory note, is the way the monarchs are treated.
In the West Kingdom, it is commonly held that the King's word is law.
This means that the King (monarch, really, we just haven't had a woman 
win yet.  Underline yet, Sir Maythen is really getting back into it)
leads the army of the West in warfare, makes policy decisions for the
good of the Kingdom, and has the final say in what happens within the realm.
I am told by those who have been privileged to attend Pennsic that the 
Kings of lands to the east have a great courtly fuss made over them, and
the officers and such end up making the real decisions.  I'm not saying
this is bad, it's just an interesting difference in the way the SCA grew
on opposite coasts.  I'm interested in the small cultural differences
(and there are many) between different Kingdoms (such as the
acceptability of wearing weapons to court, bowing to thrones when
nobody is sitting there, thrusting to the face in battle. etc)

That introductory note was rather good.  It might be a good idea to run
it by the Steward, though.  I can print off a copy and show it to Hilary 
at Thursday Bartbash.   Good gentles, please forgive my undoubtedly
geocentric attitude; if I'd discovered the SCA in a different Kingdom,
I'd think that way was the best, too.  Please feel free to correct me 
on matters of the culture of other Kingdoms, as I really do want to
know.

Coranna of Cavan
Sea Wolf Scribe



