   I'm posting this to the whole list because I took so long to do it that I
 want as many people as possible to benefit from it.  I hope none of you minds,
 and maybe you will even learn a new dance from it.

   Torvald asked me for the steps to Moonshine, and here they are:

    First, my appologies for responding so late.  I took a three-day weekend
 (Fri + Weekend) and came back to 85+ files in my reader, which took much time
 to go through between bouts of doing real work.
    Next, Moonshine.  It has its own music, and the titles I have seen it
 under are 'Svetit Luna' or 'Svetit Mesyats', and somehow translated as
 'Shining Moon'.  We called it Moonshine in Three Rivers because on the
 record we used then, there was an intro of a phrase in Russian (I presume)
 followed by a shout of 'Moonshine!' and the music would begin.  Some
 suggestions on tapes/records follow - I know that it is on at least two of
 the following, but not which two (I forgot to check at home).  Beyond these
 titles, check any Balalaika record, or Russian Folk record.
    Balalaika Melodies
    Folk Songs of Russia          both by the Balalaika Ensemble
    Play, My Balalaika            by The Andreyev Balalaika Ensemble
    The Workd of the Balalaika    by The osipov Balalaika Orchestra

  Now, the dance.  The hub of this dance, the reason I find it so much fun,
 is the spin.  You should find someone to practice it with before trying to
 teach anyone else how to do it.  I only hope I can convey the basics via
 phosphor as I have had so much trouble trying to do it in person.
  Basically, you have to imagine that you are spinning around a flagpole.
 This is the best analogy I can come up with - holding onto an upright pole
 of some kind with one hand and spinning yourself around it.  Only, in this
 dance, your partner is the pole, sort of.  Actually, when done right the
 partners balance each other and they can get up quite a bit of speed.  This
 is both the most fun part of the dance, and the hardest to do right,
 therefore the most 'dangerous'.

  The steps:
   Even though the music is in 4/4 time, the steps are in groups of 3, with
 the last beat sort of a rest.  As the music speeds up, this rest goes away.

  It can be broken up into 3 parts, the first two of which are identical.

  You begin facing your partner (this dance is not done in a line or circle
 or anything like that, but rather individual couples widely spaced about the
 dance floor) holding left hands with right arms crossed over the left and
 hanging a little limp.

  Part 1, Section 1 - Wave
    Measure 1 - Keeping hold of left hands, both partners will swing their
                 right hands out, turning their bodies a quarter turn, ending
                 up at the end in a line from right hand to right hand, facing
                 opposite directions.  In the early stages of the dance (i.e.
                 while it is slow), the feet will step in place, first right,
                 then left, then right, with the fourth beat having no motion.
                 (This is a very technical way of saying 'throw your right
                 arm behind you and take three steps in place while you do so')
    Measure 2 - Partners swing their right arms back in with a quarter turn
                 so that they end up back the way they started.  The feet do
                 three steps again, this time left, right, left. (Translation,
                 'throw your right arm back over your left taking three steps')
    Measure 3 - Same as Measure 1 (Throw right arm out)
    Measure 4 - Same as Measure 2 (Bring right arm back)
    Measure 5 - Begin same as Measure 1 and 3, except instead of just throwing
                 out the arm and stepping in place, now partners will release
                 their left hands and do a three step turn, first right, then
                 left, then right, ending up roughly facing their partner
                 across a bit of distance.  On the fourth beat of the measure,
                 clap once. (Translation, turn out and clap)
    Measure 6 - Reverse the previous measure, turning back in to partner in
                 three steps and clapping on the fourth beat. (Translation
                 un-needed)
  Part 1, Section 2 - the Spin.
    Measure 1-8 - Once the partners have clapped, they interlace arms and do
                 a forward spin for 8 measures.
                 First, the arm interlacing.  The couple stands right shoulder
                  to right shoulder, facing opposite ways.  Each puts their
                  left hand behind their back.  Each puts their right arm
                  between their partner's right arm and body (locking elbows,
                  kind of), and graps their partner's left hand.  With a good
                  strong grip, this is a very stable position.
                 Next, the spin.  When the music is slow, the best way to to
                  the spin is in groups of triple steps, starting right, left,
                  right, rest, and alternating.  But, the object (to me) of
                  this dance is the fast spin.  This will have to be practiced
                  accomplished properly - there is a tendency for one or the
                  other partner to lose balance.  Ideally, there are only two
                  motions to the fast spin per measure; one to move the inner
                  (right) foot about halfway around the center point, and the
                  other to pull the body in line with that foot, bringing the
                  outer (left) foot along.  I really cannot describe it any
                  better - you'll just have to practice it.  Believe me, it
                  is worth the effort when done right.
                 Final note - when doing the fast spin, it helps to look at a
                  stationary point while spinning, such as your partner's
                  shoulder or face.  This helps cut down on the dizzyness.
  Part 2, Section 1 - Wave
       As the partners finish spinning, they should slide apart, and turn
        their bodies to approximate the initial position of the dance.  Usually
        the first measure of this section is used to get to the position called
        for at the end of the measure (straight line from right hand to right
        hand, left hands clasped, facing opposite directions) in whatever steps
        work, leaving out the actual intermediate moves.
    Measure 1-6 - exactly the same as Part 1, Section 1
  Part 2, Section 2 - The Spin
    Measure 1-8 - exactly the same as Part 1, Section 2
  Part 3, Section 1 - Walkees!
    Measure 1-8 - instead of sliding apart, couples will modify their present
                 stance for this section.  Still right shoulder to right
                 shoulder, they un-link arms and cross right arms in front of
                 their partner, gripping respective left waists or hips.  The
                 left arm goes straight out from the shoulder, bent up at the
                 elbow (kind of like a Manual Right Turn signal for drivers or
                 bikers).  Using the triple step progression of the slow spin
                 (above, Part 1, Section 2), walk forward in a circle for 8
                 measures.
  Part 3, Section 2 - Back-bounce
    Measure 1-8 - remain in the shoulder to shoulder stance, but tighten your
                 right-hand grip.  The object here is to hop backwards in a
                 circle on your respective right feet.  This is normally done
                 by pushing off with your left foot on the first measure, and
                 then just hopping backward.  Two motions comprise this series
                 of steps - every two beats hop backward, and alternate
                 sticking your left foot straight out and bending it at the
                 knee (basically, after the first push, the left foot never
                 comes back down, it just waves in the air).
  And that's the dance - it repeats and speeds up.

  Any questions, feel free to ask.  I'm not at all sure how much sense the
   above makes - I know it very well and may be reading more into what I
   wrote than is there.  I hope you get to know and like this dance, and
   I would be delighted if you would spread it around as you see fit.

  I will be at Bhakail's Wedding event this weekend (May 14th) and at Crown
 next weekent (May 21st) if anyone in the East Kingdom (or other far travelers)
 would like a more detailed description or even a demonstration of sorts.

