It's pretty much fine as is, and I guess it doesn't hurt to keep it on
the idealistic side--that's what we want to encourage.  (But I must say
that I don't normally think of the Chivalry in quite the way that the
letter presents them.  Maybe that's just my natural skepticism kicking
in.  I'm also not sure that the Laurels and Pelicans shouldn't get equal 
billing with the Chivalry.  There may be something magic in many people's 
eyes about the idea of a Knight, but the everyday magic that keeps the
SCA running, and doing real medieval things, deserves equal respect.)

One small glitch--in the beginning of the part entitled
               How is the SCA Organized?
the first paragraph talks about the SCA, but the second jumps into a
description of feudal Europe, without indicating that the SCA context
has been left behind.  This is a little confusing, I think, when you
get down a few more paragraphs and read about how the SCA structure is
based on the feudal structure, but is not identical to it.

You might want to add a few non-professional mundane job
classifications to the list at the end--maybe Pittsburgh is kind of
unusual this way, but we have a number of housewives, some blue-collar
folks and retired people.  And of course, the ever-present students.

These are actually pretty minor points and I think the intro note is
quite good as it is.  (I do some editing and tech writing in my mundane
job, and the above suggestions are pretty much from that perspective.)

As a bureaucrat, I do wonder if perhaps someone in the hierarchy of the
Seneschalate/Steward ought to approve it before it's widely
distributed.  Just to cover all bases (and all rear ends.)  (Well, I'm
a Seneschale, but I was thinking of somebody on the Kingdom level, or
the Steward.)

Re: personae

We co-exist with Tuchux.  We are a pretty mixed gang of personae, but
one thing we don't tend to have is barbarians.  People who start out
that way usually go to the Chux.  (Note for those who haven't
encoutered Tuchux:  they are a barbarian group loosely based on John
Norman's "Gor" books.  They range from the extremely obnoxious to the
extremely authentic, but perhaps tend more towards the former.  There are
many individual Chux who are quite talented folk.  We co-exist with them 
on a more or less even keel; some of them come to our events, some of us
go to theirs.  Their fighting rules are like slightly sub-standard SCA
armor standards plus Markland rules.  They come to the Pennsic War
every year, where they drink and drum and delight in horrifying
late-period ladies. ;-)


