(To the good gentles on the mailing list: this is the second request
for info that I have gotten, so I am sending it to everyone.)

Many computer systems have mail systems that allow some kind of
"alias", or shorthand, for a list of addresses of people; when mail is
sent to this name, it is delivered to all of the addresses.  On a Unix
system, these are stored in /usr/lib/aliases.  On our main mail
machine, we have a line that looks like this:

...
incoming-sca:           elwell,zwicky,paul,diana
...

To set up local redistribution, set up such a line, substituting the
names of the local users who want to get the SCA mailing list for
ours, do whatever magic to the mail system to tell it that you have
added an alias (on Unix it's "newaliases"), then send a letter to the
mailing list maintainer (in this case, Lorimbor tells me that it is
"grof%epee.dec@decwrl.dec.com", but I don't know for sure), asking
them to unsubscribe all of the individual users, and to subscribe
"incoming-sca" (make sure to use the _whole_ address).

Doing this saves a lot of time and lowers the amount of bits shoved
around on the networks, saving many $$$ in communication costs.

		-- Paul / Tofi

