Hmmm... Herds, huh?

Well, the main "herd" in Carolingia is probably 14th-16th century, mostly
Italian and French. This is probably partly due to the fact that that's
Baron Patri's period, and a good deal of the flavor of the Barony came from
Patri. Another major reason is that dancing is pretty important in Carolingia,
and that is the period that most of our dances are from. And mostly, I suspect,
it's simply because people like the garb.

Most of the people who do persona in a big way around here do something
different. Let's see:

-- We have a couple of Vikings, one a Duke, the other our former Seneschal and
   probably the two best storytellers we have.

-- Our current Seneschal is Japanese. He isn't as utterly into persona as some,
   but his armor is Japanese, and his main weapon form katana.

-- A fair number of people do Celtic of one form or another. Given the
   general mania of the Boston area for Celtic arts, this is no great
   surprise. It does make for a rather high percentage of
   unspellable names, though.

-- Our sometime Chief Chirurgeon is Chinese; he probably does persona in a
   bigger way than anyone else here. He does all ceremonies in a proper
   Chinese manner, is very up on the history and culture of his period,
   has pretty good Chinese armor, and even has his AoA scroll in Chinese
   (which, unfortunately, he can't read).

In general, I'd say that the only real trend is that Carolingia tends
towards late period. Not quite cavalier (although we have one or two of
those, mostly fencers), but hovering on the last couple of centuries.

