Unto Kwelland-Njal, From Arval Benicoeur, Brigantia Principal Herald,
Greetings. 

What you've got is an interesting design, but not really in itself
consistent with medieval heraldic design.  Medieval heraldry didn't
run to lots of thin lines intersecting in an interesting pattern;
rather, it had a small number of large, bold, easily recognized
elements in a simple & balanced design.  Your design is quite nice,
and I agree that it makes a nice signiture-mark, but it isn't true to
the style of heraldry found in medieval Europe.  For the record, if
that design were submitted in the East, I think I would decide to
return it as too complex and for including too many thin, difficult to
distinguish lines.  

On the other hand, what you have is not very different for the
conventional representation of a snowflake: the only differences are
the fretting at the center & the absense of the bits sticking out
around the outer edge.  All in all, if this were one component of a
design, were described as a snowflake, and the design was otherwise
acceptable, I think I'd be inclined to accept it.  And since a
snowflake is a rather unusual, though perfectly good, charge, it
should be possible to get something rather simple registered.  Thus,
you might consider:

Azure, a snowflake and a chief wavy argent.

Azure, three snowflakes and a chief wavy argent.

Azure, a fess wavy argent ermined azure between three snowflakes
argent.

There are lots of possibilities which might work.  What do you think
of it?


