Subject: "novice" questions and our attitudes about newbies

Good gentles,
 
I'm very disturbed by the tone of some comments about "answering
novice questions." We were all once novices, and all once asked
questions which were born of ignorance and naivete. Please, let
us not forget in the rush to enjoy our marvelous electronic toy
that we are members of a Society in which the ideal is Chivalry
and Courtesy.
 
If we attract potential new members who see our mailings going
by, and those folk ask questions about the SCA and how it works,
Hoorah! we can certainly reach more people via electronic mail
than all the single interactions in a hour will ever reach. We
should *not* use this media to become an elitist clique of those
old-time SCAfolk who are lucky enough to know about electronic
mail.
 
Concerning the "unsolved Mysteries" show: Altho there have been
many verbal reports of problems resulting from this show, no one
has yet to make a formal report including dates of the problems,
location, or the names of people involved. If you know of such an
occurance and can substatiate it, you should report it
immediately to the Steward, who is looking for side effects of
the show.
 
And if we do get queries resulting from the show, as the Middle
Kingdom groups got inquiries following the sad Dallas Egbert
incident in late 1979, then we should view these queries as a
chance to educate, not a burden or trial.
 
I know that my personal bias is that in all our interactions we
should uphold the ideals of the Society. Can we please, as we
raise this new child that the mailgroup has blossomed into, not
fall into the traps that our cousins on other newsgroups have
plummetted into? Can we not have personal attacks, not be
unwelcoming or unfriendly, and not be cynical and unwilling to
open our eyes to new ideas? We have the most wonderful and
courteous Society in this world, and I would like our electronic
interactions to be a reflection of those ideals which we espouse
when we wear our garb and become our personas.
 
I remain, in service to our Society,
 
      siobhan

