Time for my two cents.  I am Lady Eowyn Eilonwy of Alewife Brook, a
Carolingian since the summer before Pennsic II (with about three years time
out somewhat later to see what college might have to offer), and Danulf's
sponsor in moving this list to the AI machine from his work machine at DEC
which was overloaded. AI is overloaded too, but what else is new?
    The list was moved here because the ITS community is friendly toward
such non-work-related things -- yes, gentles, these are your tax dollars at
work speeding your SCA mail over the DoD's ArpaNet -- and because COMSAT,
our mailer, is competent.  ITS is the Incompatible Timesharing System,
which is what runs here; it is -not- unix.  There are many other machines
on the connected nets which also run something other than unix.  So all
those who are interested in setting up a UUCP newsgroup should, as Lord
Danulf requested, talk to him personally rather than this whole list, and
the newsgroup organizing committee should take care to avoid steps which
would complicate receiving SCA-list mail for those of us who do not use
unix (or who do but do not receive newsgroups).
    For the gentle who was ignorant of Usenet: I think you had a BITNet
address, so you are probably aware that BITNet, CSNet, and ArpaNet form a
somewhat interlocking set of networks now more or less subsumed into the
compass of the Internet; Arpa hosts are connected by dedicated phone
cables, and probably so are most CSNet and BITNet machines.  Usenet, also
referred to as UUCP (unix-unix communication protocol), is a situation
where unices call each other up on the phone and exchange any accumulated
mail. Folks on Usenet can give you more details about the mechanics and
internal politics of this, but the vital elements are that only unix
machines can do UUCP transfers (so if your local machine runs something
else, you can't receive newsgroups), and unices -- more exactly, those who
run them -- can choose whether, and how much, to participate (which other
unices to dial up for mail exchanges, which newsgroups to accept).  In any
case, if you haven't been aware of UseNet, don't worry; you will be able to
receive mail from this list regardless of whether anything happens on the
UUCP newsgroup front.
    Enough already! Let us consign these machinations to the behind the
scenes arena they deserve, except for a possible future announcement from
those attempting to organize this newsgroup effort of a fait accompli.

    My lord Brigantia, as to your query last week as to whether a separate
list for discussing heraldry would be appropriate: My opinion is that you
should continue to conduct such discussions on the main list until you
receive a significant number of wails of protest.

