I just read Lord Eduardo Bardi's letter about his history in the
Society, and I am moved to praise him for switching from a Sword &
Sorcery persona to a good period persona.  As a herald, I have often
had the painful duty of explaining to people that, after years in the
SCA, they must now change their names.  This always causes hard
feelings, and is never any fun.

The solution, of course, is to help people pick REAL names & real
personae to go with them.  That, I believe, is the job of every
SCAdian, and especially the job of any herald.  When one of the newly
de-mundaned comes to his first event or meeting, he is always looking
for someone to help him out, someone to tell him what the SCA is for,
what it is about.  We should all make the effort to sit down with
these new members and explain the Society.  Every new member asks the
same questions: "What is a persona? How do I choose a name?"  It is at
this point that so many are given bad advice, and set up for later
problems.  Don't answer "Oh, anything you want to call yourself is
OK".  Don't answer "Gee, your D&D character has a nice name"  And
especially don't answer "Make something up"!  The Society is a
historical research & recreation group, at least to some degree, and
one of the easiest ways to encourage a little authenticity is to
answer "You should choose a real name from your period".

The added benefit of this approach is, of course, that the new member
learns from the start that research is highly valued by the Society,
that learning is always praised.  With any luck, he'll find a taste
for it, and develop a persona that really COULD have existed, take up
a craft that really was practiced in his period, and never ever ever
have to argue with the heralds over why he should be alowed to call
himself Brupwik van MacPherson.

Respectfully yours,

	Arval Benicouer, CSC.


