To: sca@ai.ai.mit.edu
Subject: Becoming a newsgroup (long)


Ok, it appears to me that there are a lot of people here who aren't real
sure about the pros/cons and procedures of becoming a Usenet newsgroup.

First, procedure. 

The first step we would need to make would be to decide whether we want to
try to be "official". An official newsgroup is one that the members of
the Usenet Backbone all agree that they will carry, and goes on Gene Spafford's
"List of Lists". This doesn't force anyone to carry the group, but most
sites will carry anything that goes on spaf's list.

The alternative is to become an "alt" group. This would be a group that
wouldn't be on The List, but would be carried at the individual site's 
discretion. The propagation of the "alt" hierarchy is around 50-60% of the
net, typically.

The advantage of being in the official hierarchy is that you get very good
propagation; since we would be a "rec" group, not every site would carry
us, but about 95% probably would.

The disadvantage is that you have to deal with the bureaucracy of the net,
at least initially. To become an official group, you should follow the
guidelines set forth by spaf, to wit:

	1) announce, in "news.groups" and anywhere else you feel relevant,
	   your intention to create this group.
	2) discuss it for a week or two, and get criticisms.
	3) make a "final form" announcement, and call for votes.
	4) collect votes for 30 days. At the end of this, if you have 100
	   more "yes" votes than "no" votes, you send a message to that
	   effect to the backbone (to spaf, I think), along with the
	   list of the voters.
	5) spaf creates the group.

This isn't quite how things officially work, since the net is supposedly
an anarchy, but this is the reality.

If you lose the vote, what to do? Either a) you go back to being a mailing
list, or b) you *then* decide to join the alt hierarchy, and send messages
around trying to convince people to carry your group. In the case of alt.sca,
it would probably be pretty easy, since we have people infiltrated well-nigh
everywhere.

*If* we decide that we want to be a newsgroup, then we probably ought to
at least try to be official. The gain in propagation is worth the hassles,
and it's always possible to fall back ten and join the alt hierarchy.

Advantages of becoming a newsgroup:
1) Visibility. Finding out about a mailing list requires *reading* the
List of Mailing Lists, and not all that many people bother. Finding
rec.sca in the newsgroups lists is probably easier for a novice netter
to deal with.

2) Load. Let's face facts. In the week or two since this mailing list
got its act together, the amount of traffic has skyrocketed. If this
keeps up, its going to eventually be noticed by MIT (mailing lists
cost a *lot* of phone time). A newsgroup is pretty expensive to the
net as a whole, but the cost is distributed to a very small amount per
site. I have heard several people on the net say that, after about
150 people, it actually becomes *cheaper* overall to have a newsgroup.
I'm not sure how that works, but if true, it's a good argument to
become the newsgroup.

Disadvantages of becoming a newsgroup:
1) Time lag. This newsletter is very nearly instantaneous; I've sent
plenty of messages to the mailing list that had replies coming in from
all over within two hours. The average propagation time is a good deal
less than a day. A newsgroup, by its very nature, has a propagation lag
of *at least* one day, and frequently it takes 3-4 days to propagate
out to the backwaters of the net. This would be annoying; part of what
is fun about the mailing list is that you can almost hold interactive
conversations.

2) Twits. We would get far more novices asking first-time questions.
This could be helped by someone putting together a "What is the SCA?"
article, and sending that to the group once a month or so, but we would
still see a lot of repetitive questions; every newsgroup does. Worse,
we would probably encounter the occasional idiot whose only knowledge
of the Society comes from "Unsolved Mysteries", who would come in like
a bull in a china shop, accusing us all of being Satanists. And there 
would be no way to get rid of him/her/it.  I'm not saying that this would 
be a common occurance, but it only takes one twit to wreck everyone else's fun.

3) Hassle. We would have to set up the gateway between ARPA and Usenet,
so that people who don't get a newsfeed could keep getting the messages.
I saw the message from someone saying that they were planning on doing
something of the sort, but my understanding is that such things are a
bit of a pain to set up.

So. This is, I think, a reasonably fair look at the issues. *If* the
concensus of opinion is that we should become a newsgroup, then I would
recommend waiting a month or two before doing it; being able to say,
"Look, we've had fifteen to twenty messages a *day* for the past two
months on this variety of different topics" would go a fair ways towards
convincing people that the group is needed (although other people would
probably gripe about "bloody high-volume newsgroups").

Think about it -- don't just make knee-jerk decisions. A mailing list and
a newsgroup are *very* different critters in their dynamics. Each has
plusses and minusses. (My personal opinion is: wait a while. If our
volume stays up, and our membership continues to rise, then think about
becoming a newsgroup when we hit 100-125).

