   Torvald:

    First, the Disco Korobushka was simply the regular Korobushka done
  to a popular contemporary (almost disco) rock tune popular at the time
  (this was circa 1978-79).  If you notice, the dance can be done to any
  tune in 4/4 time, and it helps if the tune has phrases 12 measures
  long, but this really doesn't matter.

   Second, as to your description of Korobushka - very close to accurate.
  A few points of clarification, though.  First, it would be clearer to
  say that the lady stands to the lord's right.  Second, as in many line
  dances, Korobushka may be done in a circle, but it doesn't have to be.
  For the partner-changing version, it must be done in a circle, though.
  And lastly, about the switch (parts 4-8):  as I learned it, when
  returning from the spin the first time (part 4), the couple only takes
  right hands, not both.  This makes it easier to switch places (the lady
  still goes under their right arms).  Instead of two sets of push and
  pull, we only do one, probably a little slower (it takes one measure,
  4 counts to do one push and one pull).  The same is true for the second
  spin, except that here couples do take both hands, and when they
  change places, they end up back in position to begin again.

    The partner-change version is the same as the regular version,
  except that during the last spin out and back, the lady spins out from
  her partner, and back to the lord behind her now-former partner (which
  is why this version must be done in a circle).  The new couple take
  hands, pull and push, trade places, and begin the dance again.

    If anyone out there is interested in Moonshine (if you thought
  Korobushka was energetic, wait 'till you see Moonshine!), I'll be happy
  to post its steps.  The music to both Korobushka and Moonshine is
  fairly readily available on selected Russian folk or Balalaika tapes
  (although I wish I could find a really good version of Korobushka - I
  don't have access to the old Nordskogen version, and (if you recall my
  previous treatise on the dance climate in Bhakail) you should know that
  there's no source for it here).  Trust me - if you like Korobushka, and
  you like spinning dances, and you like folk-dance-ercize, you'll love
  Moonshine.

