Greetings to all from Torvald of Jamtland.

I've seen 2 request for a description of the Korobushka & haven't seen a reply
yet so I thought I'd give it a try.  Keep in mind that I learned it last 
January, have danced it on only 2 seperate occasions, & do not specialize in
dance.

The Korobushka is a very energetic & flamboyant dance.  It is danced in a circle
of couples with the ladies on the inside & the couples facing counter-clockwise.To begin with, the couple holds their left hands together in front of them & 
their right hands behind the lady's head.  The steps are in sets of 4 so I will 
group them as such. The steps are as follows:

1: 2 steps diagonally to the right
   2 steps diagonally to the left

2: 1 step diagonally to the right
   1 step diagonally to the left
   The couple brings their right hands over the lady's head & turns to face each
     other so their right hands cross over their left hands.

3: The couple spins one full rotation to the right while moving away from each
     other (lords outward, ladies inward) ending the spin with a clap. 
 
4: The couple spins back together to the left & joins hands as before, right 
     crossing over left.

5: The couple pulls themselves together, then pushes themselves apart, then
     together again, then apart again.  

6: Next, the couple pulls themselves together, & the lord pulls the lady's left 
     arm, so she goes under their right arms & the lord & lady switch places, 
     now with their left hands crossing over their right.  This is done quickly,
     because the momentum from the switch is used to carry the couple into
     another spin away from each other as in set 3, just in the opposite
     ditection.

7: This set is exactly the same as set 5 except the couple spins to the right &
     joins hands with their left hands crossing over their right.

8: The couple does the same pull-push set as in set 6, except that in the last
     push, the lord pulls the lady's right arm so she passes under their left
     arms, rotating 270 degrees back to the beginning postion.  (Both facing
     forward, lady on the inside, left hands together in front, right hands
     together behind the lady's head.)

In set 8, on the last time through, instead of just spinning the lady back into
the original position, the lord pulls the lady's under their right arm, he 
kneels on left his left knee.  This allows the lady to sit down on the lord's
right knee when she has rotated to face the original way.  Then of course, as
with any good Russian dance, you throw up your hands & shout `Hay'.

It should be noted that the music starts at a nice brisk tempo, & speeds up
until its almost impossibly fast.

I'm not absolutely positive on the set where the couple switch places, but it
seems to work.

I hope that helped & was understandable.  Please forgive me if I've made any
errors.  I'm sure there's enough people out there that can correct me if I'm
wrong.


