Subject: Out of Period Dances

I know that different groups have very different attitudes about un-period
dances; indeed, the local attitude has changed a lot in the five years
since I joined.

Back when I first started dancing, out-of-period dances were *officially*
frowned upon, but no one really paid any attention to that. Hole in the
Wall was certainly one of the number one dances in the barony at the
time, and kidnapping was all the rage.

Lately, the attitude has changed a bit. Our repertoire has been steadily
expanding, and we're now at the point where almost no one can remember all
of the dances that *are* period. Therefore, we've been trying to slowly
move towards a more period repertoire. Hole in the Wall is taught only
rarely, and that mostly so that people know what they're doing when they
go out-barony. We're even trying to reduce our dependency on Playford
somewhat, since it's late period at best.

In place of the out-of-period stuff, we're trying to introduce some
more obscure period dances. We have about six or seven bassedances in
the repertoire now, and I'm trying to introduce new ones slowly. Also,
since we've got several members who've been around so long that they
regard *those* as too easy, we're beginning to work on some *really*
difficult dances, like 16th century canaries. Also, we've got a group
doing buffins (an ancestor of the Morris, I suspect). Geoffrey, you
want to describe the buffins a little?

As for made-up dances, that's a tangle. In principle, I have no problem
with dancing dances "in the period style". The problem is that very 
few of these dances seem to have been choreographed by people who
know the periods well enough to get something that's a *particular*
era. Thus, we wind up with bransles that have English Country moves in
them, Allemandes with Bransle movements, and so on. *This* I have a
problem with; this isn't making up new dances in period style, it's
making up a new kind of dance that is quite different. There are a few
that I've seen that looked to be pretty close to period, but not 
enough. Unfortunately, most of the people who are well-qualified to
make up "period-style" dances are violently opposed to the idea.

(Of course, I'm far from a perfect judge. I'd been under the impression
for quite some time that Maltese was entirely an SCA invention,
and was *quite* startled to find it in Orchesography. It's even 
pretty close to the way we dance it.)

In short, it's really up to the dancemaster's discretion. I just ask
that the dancemasters try to be well-informed. There really are a 
*lot* of period dances out there; we all have to work at getting
the knowledge of them around. And I ask that people really try to
make "made-up" dances bear a definite resemblance to some real
period; otherwise you just get a hash.

