  russian folkdance called Moonshine (Svetit Luna) - as well as the
  several SCA-choreographed dances like Manschaft Pavanne.
    When I returned to the SCA in Philadelphia, the first thing I got
  back into was dance.  What a shock!  I knew next to nothing about the
  dances done in the east - mostly because the bulk of Bhakail's rep. is
  either English Contry, weird Bransles I had never heard of before, or
  Bassa Dances (like Lauro, Kazzoul, and Touran).  And not one of them
  was out of period.  Our present Dance Mistress severly frowns upon
  anything that is not strictly period, including the SCA-invented ones.
    It took me a while to get used to this, a thing helped by the fact
  that I like to dance, and I was learning all sorts of wonderful dances
  (including that oh-so-difficuly Nonesuch, which really isn't).  My
  avid desire to do the russian dances and Manschaft is let out at
  Baileywicke Commons' and events, where I am the Dance Master and not
  only allow the fun dances, but actively encourage them.
    One thing I would like to know is - how does the rest of the Known
  Worlde feel about non-period-but-fun dances?  Obviously, from the
  mention of Korobushka (a russian folk dance done in a line, for which
  we developed a version that allowed partner-changing (the Disco version
  has no known creator)) here, there are people who do that dance.  I
  like it because it is rowdy and fun, and it's pseudo-period, which is
  more than enough for me.  How far will some of you go in getting fun
  dances for your people to do?  Back in Three Rivers, one of our dances
  was Strip the Willow - very non-period (done to Turkey in the Straw,
  in fact), but very entertaining.  I've heard much clammoring for it
  here in Bhakail, and in a few other groups, but Matilde (our Dance
  Mistress) goes into coniption fits if anyone mentions it in her
  presence.  (As an aside, does anyone know where to get some good music
  for Strip the Willow?  Lack of accompaniment is the only reason I
  haven't yet taught it to the Baileywicke.)
    Anyway, enough about dance.  My other two avocations are fencing and
  chroniclering (or something like that).  One of these days I will
  authorize as a fencer.  I have always wanted to fence in the SCA - it
  has distinct advantages over heavy-weapons fighting, among them the
  fact that I can actually fence with a minor degree of skill.  The
  Middle Kingom refused to even think about fencing (at least, they were
  that way up until about 5 or 6 years ago), so that was one of the nice
  differences about the East Kingdom.
     And lastly, I am about to become (any day now, really!) Bhakail's
  Chronicler.  I have never done a newsletter before, but I know several
  people who have, and who will be much help to me, I'm sure.  Still,
  it will be nice to be able to ask questions of people who have had
  serious experience with them here on this forum.

     Well, I think that that's long enough.  Farewell,

