From: justin@inmet.inmet.com (Mark Waks)
Message-Id: <8805021615.AA18614@inmet.inmet.com>
To: sca@ai.ai.mit.edu
Subject: A reply to Dani Zweig's comments


Unto Dani of the Seven Wells (and any other dancers who may be listening),

Hi.  You bring up several interesting issues, which I'll talk about one 
at a time.

Re: going through the entire repertoire every dance practise. I fully 
sympathize. I've found that this happens a lot, and it tends to drive away
the more experienced dancers, due to simple boredom. The problem here
has been similar to yours, although not quite the same. Our repertoire is,
in theory, quite large. However, the *active* repertoire has tended to
be about one dance practise long, and changes only quite slowly.

I've been working on trying to rectify this, changing the line-up a bit each
week, but that has its drawbacks; if you introduce the dances too fast, it
tends to throw the less-confident dancers badly. I've found that one new
dance each week or two seems to work pretty well.

Re: not having enough period dances. Hmm. We have a bit of an advantage
here, in the form of Ingrid Brainard. Ingrid isn't SCAdian, but she is one
of the best researchers into period dance (particularly 15th and 16th
centuries) around, and she is pretty close friends with our Baron, Patri
du Chat Gris. Dances come from her reconstructions, get passed on to 
Patri via the Cambridge Court Dancers (a performance group that they
are in), he passes them onto the current dancemaster/mistress, and they
pass it onto the general populace. Also, Patri does some reconstruction
himself, when he has time. That's a simplified description, but
largely accurate. Recently, that chain has been cut down by the Master
Class, in which the most experienced dancers in the Barony paid Ingrid
to run an intensive ten-session class in period dance. It was a fascinating,
though painful, experience. She ran it as a serious dance class, with 
forty-five minutes of warm-ups followed by an hour-and-a-half of solid
dance (and trust me, 1 1/2 hours of canaries *hurts*).

The basic problem, I guess, is simply that the 15th and 16th century
dance books are very hard to read and reconstruct from. For the later
stuff, we have Arbeau and Playford, who spell the dances out in about
the right amount of detail. The earlier manuscripts, though, tend to:
a) make lots of assumptions that are no longer valid about what people
know, and b) be completely impossible to read. Thus, a simple translation
isn't good enough. You have to have an expert deciphering the text, to
try and figure out what the author was trying to get at.

My best recommendation, I guess, would be to try to find Ingrid's written
work. I'm pretty sure that she has written a bit, although I'm not sure
what form it takes. I'll ask Patri if he has any pointers about where
one might find her reconstructions.

Re: performance pieces. Well, this has long been a point of contention
between the SCA and Ingrid. The fact is, most interesting dances of the
15th century, and a lot of the 16th, were performance pieces. They were
intended to be danced by one couple before the Presence. We have generally
*done* them as ensemble dances, though, because they are fun. They
really aren't that hard to teach; my dance practise is about 3/4 college
students, mostly freshmen and sophomores, and most of them are pretty
decent at the bassedances and ballos. (I'm about to reintroduce Verceppe;
Ingrid has changed the reconstruction, and I'm trying to spread the
corrected version). If you can convince people that they are capable
of these dances, you'll probably find that they are. The big hurdle is
just getting people to stop saying, "No *real* person could dance Lauro".

Well, the above problems seem to boil down to lack of sources. I'll
see what I can do, but most of our dances come from an oral tradition.
I'm willing to write up some plain-English directions to the bassedances,
but I suspect that directions without some amount of one-on-one teaching
won't work. Hmm. I wonder if someone in Ostgardr (or somewhere similarly
central) would be willing to sponsor a dance symposium? Getting together
a good fraction of the dancemasters of the East to talk and teach each other
would be a first step towards improving the situation. If it works, we can
see about continuing the idea on a larger scale, and compare dances with 
the rest of the world. Communication is the point here.

Here's an idea. If no one steps forward to host a symposium, how about getting
together at the war? We could hold an informal gathering, for dancemasters
(or, at least, really dedicated dancers) only, in order to keep the size
manageable. How many intense dance types are going to be at Pennsic? Do
you think that holding such a session would be worthwhile? I'd be happy
to try and organize it (it would give me something to do at the War other
than spend eight hours a day at the butts and four hours a night listening
to Clan Cambian).

(God, I don't believe it -- I'm volunteering for *another* thing.)

Re: misc stuff. What problems are you having with Heart's Ease? I didn't
find the Playford ambiguous, but I already know the dance to some extent,
so I may be making assumptions. I can, at least, tell you how we're doing
it up here.

As for fun dances driving out dull ones, I know what you mean. I've been
encountering problems with people "spicing up" some of the moderate ones.
For example, I've been forced to kill off Gathering Peascods for the
moment, because so many people were being so rowdy with the dance that it
simply wasn't *safe* anymore.

I don't know any particular choreographed galliards, though I can ask Patri.
I general, we just make up a choreography if we need one. I've generally
found that if you just start people on free galliards, introducing the
steps gradually, most people don't have too much trouble making it up
as they go along.

Well, this letter has already been unreasonably long, so I'll stop. Send
me opinions about the dance symposium idea, okay? I think that it would 
really help a pretty bad communication situation.

