Well, so far it looks like a lot of people in Pittsburgh, Boston and
the Bay Area have net access.  Not too surprising!  And I already know 
a fair number of the people who have posted so far.  Still not
surprising!  But I'll introduce myself before I go any farther (and
those of you who know me may actually be mildly surprised as I reveal 
some of my SCA history; not something I trot out very often at all . . .)

My Society name is Marian Greenleaf and I am currently the Seneschale
of the Barony-Marche of the Debateable Lands (the Pittsburgh area.)  I
went to my first event in Dearneheld (in the Midrealm; Athens, Ohio) in
A.S. X.  For a number of years I was only a lukewarm Scadian, due to
some fundamental philosophical differences with most of the rest of the
members of what was quite a small and insular shire.  My first persona
was Jeanne du Bel-Pommier, a 14th-century French peasant.  People
couldn't pronounce that name, so eventually I Anglicized it to Apple
Joan, but they still called me Marion.  When I moved to the East, I
gave up and took my present name and persona (late 15th-century English.)

During the first half of my SCA existence, I found that practicing the
arts openly caused friction with others, so I took to doing them
more or less secretly, in the company of a few friends.  I became 
a merchant in AS XV, selling my embroidery to pay the utility bills.  
(That is a good way to end up burned out on embroidery!)

Then my household and I moved to Atlantia, near the Shire of Isenfir,
but for a couple of years we didn't make contact with the Shire--our
previous experiences had not convinced us that it would be worth the
effort.  By the time we got around to it, two of us were fairly
accomplished artisans; it was a relief to discover that this didn't mean
instant ostracism.  In fact, the Shire was nearly dying, and we set
about helping to find new members and re-vitalizing it--but just as 
this was starting to get off the ground, (A.S. XVII) I decided to move to
Pittsburgh, for mundane reasons.

The boyfriend that I moved here to live with (now my fiance), and many
of the people that I met here through him, were and are active
Scadians.  I found the BMDL to be an open and friendly group, not very
hidebound, not at all heavy with peers, and full of interesting people.
I became deputy Minister of Arts in short order (since someone was
needed to do the paperwork end of things) and have not slowed down
since.  After my previous SCA experience, the BMDL was incredibly open
and enthusiastic.  I will always be grateful for this!

Although I have been pretty thoroughly sidetracked into administration,
I have many active interests in the arts and sciences.  Among them are
illumination (I am an East Kingdom scribe), poetry, vocal music, period
cookery (and the use of period botanicals generally), and medieval
buildings and building techniques.  I have taught classes on most of
these subjects, and also on autocratting and suchlike.

Encouraged by the acceptance of female fighters here, I decided to find
out why rattan was so fascinating, and authorized several years ago.
I am not very good, except in melees, but it's fun.  I also shoot
archery, at which I am solidly mediocre (even when in practice.)

I enjoy performance dance, and a few years ago (before our current
Dancemaster, Dani (who has introduced himself here) joined) we used to
do a fair amount of it here.  But some of the regulars moved, and
others (like me) took on increasingly heavy administrative duties and
had to cut out a lot of other activities.  I think that dance, like so
many other SCA things, goes in cycles and that in a couple of years it
will be more interesting to be a dancer here.  The notion of soliciting
dance advice on the net is wonderful!

After all these years, I am still enthusiastic, still fairly trusting,
and still a dedicated artist, with or without the SCA.  The SCA has
given me many true friendships and opportunities to grow.  I try to
pass along such benefits to others in my SCA career.

Mundanely, I have been an artifical intelligence researcher at
Carnegie-Mellon University for the past four years.  Last year I
enrolled in a PhD program in Computational Linguistics, and my job
became my assistantship.  The first year of grad school has been a very
interesting thing to mix with being Seneschale, and I find that I am
not unhappy that my term of office will be up this summer.

I have opinions on heraldry, too, but they are perhaps not as
reasonable as they should be (though I bear no grudges against any
individuals.)  One of these days, I am sure that I will design a device
that  a) will not get bounced at the Laurel level  b) I will like  and
c) the local herald will actually submit instead of losing.  After all,
I've only been trying for four years.

All in all, I figure that since I allow myself the luxury of being
snotty about poetry (and I am, though not about much else--but I may be
corrected on this point by some other gentle, I suppose ;-), I should
allow that the heralds may be snotty about heraldry.  There is really a
fair amount of practical justification for keeping heraldy "pure."  I
just happen to find some of the process to be unnecessarily arbitrary.

