Hi Justin,

        Pleased to meet you.  I'm Dani of the Seven Wells.  I'm the current
Dancemaster for the Barony Marche of the Debateable Lands (Mundanely
Pittsburgh).  My interests include music (vocal and instrumental), dance and
archery.

Our entire dance repertoire consists (for practical purposes) of less than 40
dances, most of which we do semi-regularly.  (It's a problem:  the same dances
get done every week.)  A breakdown of these dances (I could dig up specific
titles) is revealing:

Period Non-English (Bransles, etc.):  About half a dozen.
Period English Country:  About half a dozen.
Non-Period English Country: About a dozen.
SCA choreographies:  About half a dozen.
International Folk Dances:  About half a dozen.

(I should distinguish between dances which the regular dancers do and dances
which get pulled out at events so that even the people who almost never dance
can dance.  The latter list is much shorter:  Bransle d'officiale, Carolingian
Pavan, Earl of Salisbury Pavan, Hole in the Wall, Horses Bransle, [SCA] Maltese
Bransle, Sellenger's Round, Gae Gordons, Korobushka.)

An obvious question suggests itself:

a)  Why so few Period dances?

As far as the non-English dances are concerned, there doesn't seem to be that
much material (suggestions would be appreciated!) that falls between the boring
basic dances (double to the left, double to the right, repeat ad infinitum) and
dances which seem to be primarily meant as performance pieces (Verceppe,
Genevra).

As for the English Country dances, fun dances drive out dull ones, and the
later ones tend to be more fun.  (This may also have something to do with why
more people get up to do Korobushka than Staines Morris :-)

Making matters somewhat worse, we currently have a dancemaster who isn't
finding time to research new period dances.  (Can anyone suggest some good
references?  I recently tried to pull out Heart's Ease, for example, but we
couldn't disambiguate the Playford instructions.  And I didn't want to just go
with a best-guess, because we do enough dances differently from the rest of the
known world already as it is.)

(Also, can anyone suggest a good choreographed galliard?  I think many people
would enjoy galliarding who wouldn't feel up to improvising to music.)

