Greetings to all from Arval Benicoeur, Brigantia Principal Herald.

In response to my suggestion that we start a discussion of matters
heraldic on this net, I have received many letters, and I thank you
all.  In general, do people think that such discussions should be
dealt with as separate mailing lists, or broadcast through Lord
Danulf's SCAnet?

I received the following (editted):

From Lady Coranna of Cavan of the Province of the Southern Shores,
Principality of the Mists:

   I'm particularly interested in visual differencing, as this is a 'grey
   area'.  (feel free to post this if you think it would be of general
   interest)  For example, two devices were passed, as:

   Sable, a winged fox rampant within a bordure argent    and
   Purpure, a winged fox rampant to sinister within a bordure argent.

   The black one passed first, and its bearer (Eric Foxworthy) met the 
   bearer of the second device on the field at Pennsic.  From a distance, 
   he said, it looked exactly like his own, as the purple was very dark.  
   These two devices have a clear two points of difference, but Eric argues
   that rampant and rampant to sinister do not have a sufficient visual
   difference for the second device to have passed.  Arguing past history
   may not be useful, but I wanted another Herald's opinion.

   Coranna of Cavan, Sea Wolf Scribe (sun!quintus!laurie)


The Rules for Submission to count sufficient difference between these
arms.  The basic requirement is, of course, two major points of
difference.  Tincture of field and posture of the beast each count for
a full point.

I agree that the rampant & rampant reversed do not really differ by a
full visual point, and, indeed, I have been trying for some time to
convince the College of Arms.  In medieval armory, there does not
seem to have been any difference accorded for dexter/sinister
mirroring: frequently in works of art, the same set of arms will be
found facing both ways.  For example, on alterpieces, arms such as
"Gules, a bull rampant Or" would be shown on both sides of the central
panel, with both bulls facing inward.  Artists found this more
appropriate, and there is no reason to belive that heralds considered
this to change the arms in any way.  From a more practical standpoint,
if you make a good banner or standard with your arms on it, then you
certainly want the charges on both sides, and you clearly want both
your beast facing to the front as you ride onto the field...

In my opinion, the only time that we should accord any difference for
the direction a charge is facing is when there is some other element
of the design which reinforces the asymettry.  For example, "Argent,
two wolves combattant azure" and "Argent, two wolves rampant addorsed
azure" clearly differ by a point.

The College is currently reviewing the methods used to count
difference, and one of the proposed revisions would do away with this
distinction.  If you think this is a good idea, my Lady, I urge you to
write to the lady Laurel Queen of Arms.  She is even now preeparing a
revised draft of the Rules for Submission, and would appreciate all
input.  Your example is an excellent illustration of how our Rules
fail.


Yours in discussion,

Arval / Brigantia.





